{"title_page": "Rich Vial", "text_new": "<ref></ref>{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix = \n | name         = Rich Vial\n | honorific-suffix = \n | image        = Rich Vial.jpg\n | alt          = \n | state_house = Oregon\n | district     = [[Oregon's 26th House district|26th]]\n | term_start   = January 9, 2017\n | term_end     = January 14, 2019\n | predecessor  = [[John Davis (Oregon politician)|John Davis]]\n | successor    = [[Courtney Neron]]\n | office1 = \n | term_start1 = \n | term_end1 = \n | predecessor1 = \n | successor1 = \n | prior_term   = \n | birth_name         = \n | birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1954|9|28}}\n | birth_place        = [[Lynwood, California|Lynnwood]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n | death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n | death_place        = \n | resting_place      = \n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | citizenship        = \n | nationality        = \n | party              = [[Nonpartisan (United States)|Nonpartisan]]\n | spouse             = \n | children = \n | residence          = [[Scholls, Oregon]]\n | education          = \n | alma_mater         = [[Brigham Young University]]<br/>[[Willamette University College of Law]]\n | occupation         = \n | religion           = \n}}\n'''Armand Richard Vial''' (born September 28, 1954) is an American lawyer and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician who served in the [[Oregon House of Representatives]]. He represented the 26th district, which covers parts of southern [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]] and the west end of [[Clackamas County, Oregon|Clackamas County]].\n\n==Biography==\nVial was born in [[Lynwood, California]]. He attended [[Brigham Young University]], from where he graduated in 1978, and the [[Willamette University College of Law]]. He has served on the Washington County Land Use Advisory Committee, and the [[Clean Water Services]] Advisory Committee.<ref name=votesmart/>\n\nHe ran for the state House in 2016. During his campaign, a complaint filed by Kathleen Stuart, the director of a state Democratic Party organization, alleged that Vial did not reside in the district he was campaigning to represent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/322693-202436-complaint-alleges-gop-candidate-rich-vial-lives-outside-hd-26|title=Complaint alleges GOP candidate Rich Vial lives outside HD 26|author=Townsley, Nancy|newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]]|date=September 13, 2016|accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref> The case was resolved in Vial's favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pamplinmedia.com/ht/118-hillsboro-tribune-opinion/327299-206439-endorsement-vial-should-get-voters-nod-in-house-district-26-|title=ENDORSEMENT: Vial should get voters' nod in House District 26|publisher=[[Hillsboro Tribune]]|date=October 13, 2016|accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref> He defeated Democratic candidate Ray Lister in the general election.<ref name=results>{{cite web|url=http://sos.oregon.gov/elections/Documents/results/november-2016-results.pdf|title=November 8, 2016, General Election Abstract of Votes|publisher=[[Oregon Secretary of State]]|accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nVial is the former Chair of the Washington County Planning Commission and has previously served as Chair of the [[Hillsboro School District#Groner|Groner School District]] Board and the [[Washington County Fair (Oregon)|Washington County Fair Board]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregonlegislature.gov/vial/Pages/biography.aspx|title=Representative Rich Vial}}</ref>\n\nVial was defeated in 2018 by [[Courtney Neron]], a Democrat. After leaving the state legislature, Vial served as the Oregon Deputy Secretary of State under [[Bev Clarno]] from April 2019 to January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/politics/2020/01/rich-vial-resigns-as-deputy-oregon-secretary-of-state.html|title=Rich Vial resigns as deputy Oregon secretary of state|date=January 9, 2020|first1=Betsy|last1=Hammond|first2=Rob|last2=Davis|work=[[The Oregonian]]|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVial and his wife, Paula, who have been married since 1975, have 13 children, including 7 [[Vietnam]]ese refugee children, and 41 grandchildren.<ref name=votesmart>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/168066/richard-vial#.WH1nEnfMwZc|title=Richard Vial's Biography|publisher=Project VoteSmart|accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.richvial.org Campaign website]\n* [https://www.oregonlegislature.gov/vial Legislative website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vial, Rich}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Oregon House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Oregon lawyers]]\n[[Category:Nonpartisan]]\n[[Category:People from Lynwood, California]]\n[[Category:People from Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Willamette University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:School board members in Oregon]]\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix = \n | name         = Rich Vial\n | honorific-suffix = \n | image        = Rich Vial.jpg\n | alt          = \n | state_house = Oregon\n | district     = [[Oregon's 26th House district|26th]]\n | term_start   = January 9, 2017\n | term_end     = January 14, 2019\n | predecessor  = [[John Davis (Oregon politician)|John Davis]]\n | successor    = [[Courtney Neron]]\n | office1 = \n | term_start1 = \n | term_end1 = \n | predecessor1 = \n | successor1 = \n | prior_term   = \n | birth_name         = \n | birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1954|9|28}}\n | birth_place        = [[Lynwood, California|Lynnwood]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n | death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n | death_place        = \n | resting_place      = \n | resting_place_coordinates = \n | citizenship        = \n | nationality        = \n | party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n | spouse             = \n | children = \n | residence          = [[Scholls, Oregon]]\n | education          = \n | alma_mater         = [[Brigham Young University]]<br/>[[Willamette University College of Law]]\n | occupation         = \n | religion           = \n}}\n'''Armand Richard Vial''' (born September 28, 1954) is an American lawyer and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician who served in the [[Oregon House of Representatives]]. He represented the 26th district, which covers parts of southern [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington County]] and the extreme west of [[Clackamas County, Oregon|Clackamas County]].\n\n==Biography==\nVial was born in [[Lynwood, California]]. He attended [[Brigham Young University]], from where he graduated in 1978, and the [[Willamette University College of Law]]. He has served on the Washington County Land Use Advisory Committee, and the [[Clean Water Services]] Advisory Committee.<ref name=votesmart/>\n\nHe ran for the state House in 2016. During his campaign, a complaint filed by Kathleen Stuart, the director of a state Democratic Party organization, alleged that Vial did not reside in the district he was campaigning to represent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/322693-202436-complaint-alleges-gop-candidate-rich-vial-lives-outside-hd-26|title=Complaint alleges GOP candidate Rich Vial lives outside HD 26|author=Townsley, Nancy|newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]]|date=September 13, 2016|accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref> The case was resolved in Vial's favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pamplinmedia.com/ht/118-hillsboro-tribune-opinion/327299-206439-endorsement-vial-should-get-voters-nod-in-house-district-26-|title=ENDORSEMENT: Vial should get voters' nod in House District 26|publisher=[[Hillsboro Tribune]]|date=October 13, 2016|accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref> He defeated Democratic candidate Ray Lister in the general election.<ref name=results>{{cite web|url=http://sos.oregon.gov/elections/Documents/results/november-2016-results.pdf|title=November 8, 2016, General Election Abstract of Votes|publisher=[[Oregon Secretary of State]]|accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nVial is the current Chair of the Washington County Planning Commission and has previously served as Chair of the [[Hillsboro School District#Groner|Groner School District]] Board and the [[Washington County Fair (Oregon)|Washington County Fair Board]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oregonlegislature.gov/vial/Pages/biography.aspx|title=Representative Rich Vial}}</ref>\n\nVial was defeated in 2018 by [[Courtney Neron]], a Democrat. After leaving the state legislature, Vial served as the Oregon Deputy Secretary of State under [[Bev Clarno]] from April 2019 to January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/politics/2020/01/rich-vial-resigns-as-deputy-oregon-secretary-of-state.html|title=Rich Vial resigns as deputy Oregon secretary of state|date=January 9, 2020|first1=Betsy|last1=Hammond|first2=Rob|last2=Davis|work=[[The Oregonian]]|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVial and his wife, Paula, who have been married since 1975, have 13 children, including 7 [[Vietnam]]ese refugee children, and 41 grandchildren.<ref name=votesmart>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/168066/richard-vial#.WH1nEnfMwZc|title=Richard Vial's Biography|publisher=Project VoteSmart|accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.richvial.org Campaign website]\n* [https://www.oregonlegislature.gov/vial Legislative website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vial, Rich}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Oregon House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Oregon lawyers]]\n[[Category:Oregon Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Lynwood, California]]\n[[Category:People from Washington County, Oregon]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Willamette University College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:School board members in Oregon]]\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n", "name_user": "Timtrickey", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated party registration (changed to nonpartisan) and fixed some grammatical errors.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rich_Vial"}
{"title_page": "Krabby Patty", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional hamburger in the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants}}\n{{pp-sock|small=yes}}\nA '''Krabby Patty''' is a [[hamburger]] sold by the fictional restaurant the [[Krusty Krab]] in the animated television series ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]''. Created by the restaurant's founder and manager [[Mr. Krabs|Eugene Krabs]], it is what the main character SpongeBob cooks throughout his job as a fry cook, and the restaurant's trademark food and most famous burger in Bikini Bottom. A prominent [[running gag]] throughout the series is Krabs' nemesis [[Plankton and Karen#Plankton|Sheldon Plankton]] trying to steal the Krabby Patty secret formula. This running gag was given a backstory in the special \"[[Friend or Foe (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Friend or Foe]]\", where it is revealed that Krabs and Plankton created the Krabby Patty to compete with the health-violating restaurant Stinky Burgers.\n\n== Role in ''SpongeBob SquarePants'' ==\nKrabby Patties make their debut appearance in ''SpongeBob SquarePants''{{'}} pilot episode \"[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]\" and have had many different variations throughout the show's run.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/5/1/18524161/spongebob-squarepants-anniversary-20-years-episodes |title=SpongeBob SquarePants' 20 years of brilliance, explained in 3 episodes |first=Allegra |last=Frank |date=1 May 2019 |work=Vox |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Krabby Patty burger is a menu item sold by the [[Krusty Krab]] as a [[fast food]] product.<ref>{{cite episode |title=The Play's the Thing |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=7 |number=138a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=26 March 2010 |credits=Writers: [[Luke Brookshier]], Nate Cash, [[Steven Banks]] |language=en}}</ref> It is considered to be one of the most successful food in Bikini Bottom.<ref name=\"Hist\">{{cite episode |title=Krusty Krab Training Video |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=3 |number=50b |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=May 10, 2002 |credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; [[C. H. Greenblatt|Greenblatt, C. H.]]; [[Kent Osborne|Osborne, Kent]] (writers)}}</ref> The Krabby Patty formula is a closely guarded [[trade secret]], and rival restaurateur Plankton's futile attempts at acquiring the secret formula is a major [[running gag|recurring theme]] throughout the series. These attempts always backfire on him, but nevertheless he succeeded in ''[[The SpongeBob SquarePants Movie]]'' due to Mr. Krabs' execution.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/06/07/spongebob-squarepants-will-stop-annihilation-of-undersea-world-in-new-broadway-musical-6692251/ |title=SpongeBob SquarePants leaves Bikini Bottom behind for a brand new broadway show |last=Gamp |first=Joe |work=Metro News |date=7 June 2017 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The Krusty Krab usually attracts customers from Bikini Bottom because of the Krabby Patty's renowned taste and the fact that Plankton's restaurant, the Chum Bucket, has a menu consisting of mostly inedible [[chumming|chum]].<ref>{{cite episode |title=Chum Bucket Supreme |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=6 |number=122a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=10 May 2002 |credits=Writers: Sean Charmatz, Dani Michaeli |language=en}}</ref> Due to the lack of viable competition, Mr. Krabs is generally free to engage in [[price gouging]], a practice he has been known to do throughout the show.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Krabby Land |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=3 |number=57a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=3 April 2004 |credits=Writers: [[Luke Brookshier]], Nate Cash, [[Steven Banks]] |language=en}}</ref> Sometimes the Krusty Krab is shown to have a [[drive-thru]] to serve krabby patties seen in the episodes \"Driven to Tears\" and \"Drive Thru\" as well as ''[[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water]]''.<ref>{{cite episode |title=The Krusty Sponge |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=5 |number=89a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=10 May 2002 |credits=Writers: Paul Tibbitt, Kent Osborne, Mark O'Hare |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/feb/03/spongebob-movie-sponge-out-of-water-first-look-review |title=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water first look review \u2013 superhero slugfest drags a good sequel down |first=Jordan |last=Hoffman |date=3 February 2015 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> It is noted by Mr. Krabs that the Krusty Krab and the Krabby Patty is clean and disease-free.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Fungus Among Us |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=5 |number=83c |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=29 September  2007 |credits=Writers: Casey Alexander, Zeus Cervas, Richard Pursel |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Ingredients ==\nThe Krabby Patty is made out of a [[Frozen food|frozen]] hamburger with buns, the patty, [[pickled cucumber|pickles]], [[lettuce]], [[tomato]]es, [[cheese]],<ref>{{cite episode |title=Boss for a Day |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=12 |number=258a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=17 October 2019 |credits=Writers: Andrew Goodman |language=en}}</ref> [[ketchup]], [[Mustard (condiment)|mustard]],<ref>{{cite episode |title=Mustard O' Mine |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=11 |number=232a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=10 May 2018 |credits=Writers: Kaz |language=en}}</ref> and [[onions]]<ref>{{cite episode |title=The Way of the Sponge |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=8 |number=166b |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=25 November 2011 |credits=Writers: Casey Alexander, Zeus Cervas, Derek Iversen, Andrew Goodman |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/binging-babish-spongebob-krabby-patty/ |title=Some genius finally figured out how to make the perfect Krabby Patty |last=Rolli |first=Bryan |date=31 May 2017 |work=The Daily Dot |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and with a Krabby Patty secret formula, though said secret formula has never been revealed in the series. In the episode \"[[Just One Bite]],\" the Krusty Krab is revealed to have a \"patty vault\" that contains many Krabby Patties.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mashable.com/article/spongebob-memes-explained/ |title=Why is SpongeBob so damn meme-able? |first=Chloe |last=Bryan |work=Mashable |date=8 April 2018 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Krusty Krab's menu, the Galley Grub, consists mostly of ordinary fast food items, such as french fries and sodas. Its signature sandwich, the Krabby Patty, is celebrated, to a comic degree, by the citizens of Bikini Bottom. In ''[[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water]]'', Mr. Krabs states: \"The Krabby Patty is what ties us all together! Without it, there will be a complete breakdown of social order!\"<ref>{{cite film|title=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|title-link=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|type=film|date=February 6, 2015|publisher=Paramount Pictures|author=[[Paul Tibbitt|Tibbitt, Paul]] (director)|others=[[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Aibel, Jonathan; Berger, Glenn]] (writers)}}</ref> The sandwich comprises two buns, with the patty, lettuce, cheese, onions, tomatoes, ketchup, mustard, and pickles between them, (in that order).<ref>{{cite episode |title=Pickles |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=1 |number=6b |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=21 August 1999 |credits=[[Steven Fonti|Fonti, Steve]]; Mitchell, Chris; Burns, Peter (writers)}}</ref>\n=== Theories ===\nThe formula has been hinted at but remained a mystery throughout the series. A running gag is Plankton's obsession with obtaining it as a way to produce the sandwiches and attract customers to his across-the-street restaurant, the Chum Bucket.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2018/03/the-latest-spongebob-meme-features-the-krusty-krab-vs-chum-bucket-rivalry |title=The Latest Spongebob Meme Features the Krusty Krab vs. Chum Bucket Rivalry |last=Barner |first=Katherine |work=Complex |date=18 March 2018 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The recipe of the patty is a closely guarded [[trade secret]], which have led viewers to speculate about its contents.<ref name=\"FoodbeastMSG\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foodbeast.com/news/krabby-patty-crab-meat/ |title=People Think The Krabby Patty's Secret Was Crab Meat, And It Makes So Much Sense |last=Rocha |first=Isai |date=18 July 2017 |access-date=20 July 2019 |website=Foodbeast |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171726/https://www.foodbeast.com/news/krabby-patty-crab-meat/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"MetroPowder\">{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Sam |title=People think that the secret ingredient in SpongeBob Squarepants' Krabby Patty is cocaine |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/01/14/people-think-that-the-secret-ingredient-in-spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-is-cocaine-8343117/ |website=Metro |publisher=DMG Media |access-date=22 July  2019 |date=14 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171720/https://metro.co.uk/2019/01/14/people-think-that-the-secret-ingredient-in-spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-is-cocaine-8343117/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> Several fan theories have been formed to guess the secret ingredient.<ref name=\"SRMeat&Powder\">{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/spongebob-theory-krabby-patty-ingredients/ |title=SpongeBob Theory: What Are Krabby Patties Actually Made Of? |last=Hood |first=Cooper |date=March 16, 2019 |access-date=July 20, 2019 |website=Screen Rant |publisher=Valnet Inc. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171719/https://screenrant.com/spongebob-theory-krabby-patty-ingredients/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NewsweekPowder\">{{cite web |last1=Asarch |first1=Steven |title=Secret Ingredient In Krabby Patty? Cocaine! Says Internet |url=https://www.newsweek.com/krabby-patty-secret-ingredient-poseidon-powder-cocaine-spongebob-1294303 |website=Newsweek |access-date=22 July 2019 |date=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171719/https://www.newsweek.com/krabby-patty-secret-ingredient-poseidon-powder-cocaine-spongebob-1294303 |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to series animator [[Vincent Waller]], \"there is absolutely no meat in the Krabby Patty. There's no animal product in there\", something which was always planned by series creator [[Stephen Hillenburg]].<ref name=\"CinemablendVegan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/1684060/whats-in-a-krabby-patty-heres-what-the-spongebob-producer-knows |title=What's In A Krabby Patty? Here's What The Spongebob Producer Knows |last=Joest |first=Mick |date=22 July 2017 |access-date=20 July 2017 |work=CinemaBlend |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725193849/http://www.cinemablend.com/television/1684060/whats-in-a-krabby-patty-heres-what-the-spongebob-producer-knows |archive-date=July 25, 2017 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> [[Mr. Lawrence]], a show writer and Plankton's voice actor, explained that the show's writers are not allowed to depict [[fish as food]]; he stated that there is no meat served in Bikini Bottom except at the Chum Bucket.<ref name=\"EliteVegan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/entertainment/spongebob-krabby-patty-theory-formula/2024695 |title=Krabby Patty Formula, According To 'Spongebob' Cast Members, Isn't What You Expected |last=Kolokathis |first=Tina |date=23 July 2017 |access-date=20 July 2019 |website=Elite Daily |publisher=Bustle Digital Group |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719085317/https://www.elitedaily.com/entertainment/spongebob-krabby-patty-theory-formula/2024695 |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> [[Tom Kenny]], the voice actor for SpongeBob, joked: \"Krabby Patties are [[hummus]]!\"<ref name=\"EliteVegan\" /> Some commentators suggest that there is actually no secret ingredient, pointing to Mr. Krabs' miserliness. A writer for [[Hollywood.com]] believes that it is \"all a ruse that crafty Mr. Krabs came up with in order to stop Plankton from focusing on [t]he Chum Bucket. It's legitimately brilliant marketing!\"<ref name=\"HollywoodPowder\">{{cite web |title=We FINALLY Know What The Krabby Patty Secret Formula Is From 'SpongeBob'! |url=http://www.hollywood.com/tv/we-finally-know-what-the-spongebob-krabby-patty-secret-formula-is-60577938/ |access-date=22 July 2019 |date=5 May 2016 |work=Hollywood.com |last=Tinubu |first=Aramide |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615091801/http://www.hollywood.com/tv/we-finally-know-what-the-spongebob-krabby-patty-secret-formula-is-60577938/ |archive-date=15 June 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> The episode \"Patty Caper\" shows that there is truly a secret ingredient in the Krabby Patty, which is delivered to the restaurant with high security.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Patty Caper |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=6 |number=108a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=5 August 2008 |credits=Writers: Casey Alexander, Zeus Cervas, Eric Shaw |language=en}}</ref> On the possibility that the secret Krabby Patty formula will be revealed in future episodes, Waller said in 2017 that he \"would not count on it\".<ref>{{cite tweet |number=881707307071033350 |user=VincentWaller72 |title=I would not count on it. |last=Waller |first=Vincent |date=2 July 2017 |access-date=28 July 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.is/eZAeW |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> In 2019, Waller stated that Hillenburg, who died in 2018, is the only person to have seen it.<ref>{{cite tweet |number=1087776914343845888 |user=VincentWaller72 |title=Yes, but no human has seen it, other than Steve. |last=Waller |first=Vincent |date=22 January 2019 |access-date=28 July 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.is/6YMGQ |archive-date=28 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Real-life inspirations ==\nPublications such as ''[[USA Today]]'' have named it among other fictional foods that many have wanted to exist in real life,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2019/06/13/krabby-patties-butterbeer-and-more-9-fictional-foods-we-want/1442722001/ |last=Ali |first=Rasha |title=Order up: Krabby Patties, Apollo Bars and other fictional foods we wish were real |date=13 June 2019 |work=USA Today |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> but according to the ''[[New York Daily News]]'', there are four restaurants which serve a similar burger to the seen one in the show. These burgers include the Snow Crab Crispy Rice, Phuket Fantasy, Angry Crab Benedict, and Soft Shell Crab Taco.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/eats/fried-crab-spongebob-fans-article-1.2092796 |title=SpongeBob inspiring you to find your own Krabby Patty? 5 New York eateries with fresh takes on crab sandwiches |first=Gina |last=Pace |work=New York Daily News |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Krabby Patties have also inspired real life gummy confectionery treats, primarily in [[New England]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Buchanan |first1=Jesse |title=New Southington shop offers kids activities, nostalgic candy |url=http://www.myrecordjournal.com/News/Southington/Southington-News/Candy-shop-bookstore-kids-venue-opens-on-Center-Street-in-Southington.html |access-date=2 December 2019 |work=Meriden Record Journal |date=9 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Finaldi |first1=Laura |title=Finaldi: Express, Candy Barrel leaving Sarasota Square mall |url=https://www.heraldtribune.com/news/20190619/finaldi-express-candy-barrel-leaving-sarasota-square-mall |access-date=2 December 2019 |work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=19 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In 2008, a doctor with [[Texas A&M Health Science Center College of Medicine]] warned parents to be aware of where the candy their child consumes is produced due to contamination then found in Chinese milk; Spongebob Gummy Krabby Patties were among those candies produced in [[China]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sigman |first1=Ashlea |title=Doctor: Be Cautious of Candy Made in China |url=https://www.kbtx.com/home/headlines/33617284.html |access-date=2 December 2019 |work=KBTX-TV |date=30 October 2008 |language=en}}</ref> In 2019, a reporter with the student newspaper of [[Capital University]] gave the gummy candies a rating of a 2 out of 10 in their review of Halloween candy.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pasco |first1=Shirleeah |title=Not all candies are created equal: Halloween candy reviews |url=http://cuchimes.com/10/2019/halloween-candy-reviews/ |access-date=2 December 2019 |work=The Chimes |date=24 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Krabby Patty has been used by [[Katy Perry]] as a second costume on the red carpet at New York's [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sea.mashable.com/entertainment/3656/katy-perry-former-chandelier-changed-into-a-hamburger-at-the-met-gala |title=Katy Perry, former chandelier, changed into a hamburger at the Met Gala |last=Lieu |first=Johnny |date=7 May 2019 |work=Mashable SEA |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In [[SpongeBob SquarePants (musical)|''The SpongeBob Musical'']], the Krabby Patty was portrayed by an actor on stage at the [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/meet-krabby-patty-actor-spongebob-squarepants-musical-article-1.3666281 |title=Playing a giant Krabby Patty in 'SpongeBob SquarePants' musical can leave you feeling fried |first=Gina |last=Salamone |work=New York Daily News |date=30 November 2017 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Various merchandise depicts Spongebob and the Krabby Patty such as HipDot<ref>{{cite web |last=Zimmerman |first=Kelsi |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/the-hipdot-x-spongebob-collection-is-the-best-thing-since-the-invention-of-the-krabby-patty-18007378 |title=SpongeBob Is The Latest Beauty Influencer Thanks To The HipDot x SpongeBob Makeup Collection |work=Elite Daily |date=14 June 2019 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and Dog Toy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.geekalerts.com/spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-dog-toy/ |title=SpongeBob SquarePants Krabby Patty Dog Toy |work=Geek Alerts |first=Ryan |last=Cooper |date=3 October 2018 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Krusty Krab]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{SpongeBob SquarePants}}\n\n[[Category:SpongeBob SquarePants]]\n\n[[Category:Fictional foods]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1999]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional hamburger in the animated series SpongeBob SquarePants}}\n{{pp-sock|small=yes}}\nA '''Krabby Patty''' is a [[hamburger]] sold by the fictional restaurant the [[Krusty Krab]] in the animated television series ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]''. Created by the restaurant's founder and manager [[Mr. Krabs|Eugene Krabs]], it is what the main character SpongeBob cooks throughout his job as a fry cook, and the restaurant's trademark food and most famous burger in Bikini Bottom. A prominent [[running gag]] throughout the series is Krabs' nemesis [[Plankton and Karen#Plankton|Sheldon Plankton]] trying to steal the Krabby Patty secret formula. This running gag was given a backstory in the special \"[[Friend or Foe (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Friend or Foe]]\", where it is revealed that Krabs and Plankton created the Krabby Patty to compete with the health-violating restaurant Stinky Burgers.\n\n== Role in ''SpongeBob SquarePants'' ==\nKrabby Patties make their debut appearance in ''SpongeBob SquarePants''{{'}} pilot episode \"[[Help Wanted (SpongeBob SquarePants)|Help Wanted]]\" and have had many different variations throughout the show's run.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2019/5/1/18524161/spongebob-squarepants-anniversary-20-years-episodes |title=SpongeBob SquarePants' 20 years of brilliance, explained in 3 episodes |first=Allegra |last=Frank |date=1 May 2019 |work=Vox |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Krabby Patty burger is a menu item sold by the [[Krusty Krab]] as a [[fast food]] product.<ref>{{cite episode |title=The Play's the Thing |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=7 |number=138a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=26 March 2010 |credits=Writers: [[Luke Brookshier]], Nate Cash, [[Steven Banks]] |language=en}}</ref> It is considered to be one of the most successful food in Bikini Bottom.<ref name=\"Hist\">{{cite episode |title=Krusty Krab Training Video |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=3 |number=50b |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=May 10, 2002 |credits=[[Aaron Springer|Springer, Aaron]]; [[C. H. Greenblatt|Greenblatt, C. H.]]; [[Kent Osborne|Osborne, Kent]] (writers)}}</ref> The Krabby Patty formula is a closely guarded [[trade secret]], and rival restaurateur Plankton's futile attempts at acquiring the secret formula is a major [[running gag|recurring theme]] throughout the series. These attempts always backfire on him, but nevertheless he succeeded in ''[[The SpongeBob SquarePants Movie]]'' due to Mr. Krabs' execution.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/06/07/spongebob-squarepants-will-stop-annihilation-of-undersea-world-in-new-broadway-musical-6692251/ |title=SpongeBob SquarePants leaves Bikini Bottom behind for a brand new broadway show |last=Gamp |first=Joe |work=Metro News |date=7 June 2017 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The Krusty Krab usually attracts customers from Bikini Bottom because of the Krabby Patty's renowned taste and the fact that Plankton's restaurant, the Chum Bucket, has a menu consisting of mostly inedible [[chumming|chum]].<ref>{{cite episode |title=Chum Bucket Supreme |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=6 |number=122a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=10 May 2002 |credits=Writers: Sean Charmatz, Dani Michaeli |language=en}}</ref> Due to the lack of viable competition, Mr. Krabs is generally free to engage in [[price gouging]], a practice he has been known to do throughout the show.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Krabby Land |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=3 |number=57a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=3 April 2004 |credits=Writers: [[Luke Brookshier]], Nate Cash, [[Steven Banks]] |language=en}}</ref> Sometimes the Krusty Krab is shown to have a [[drive-thru]] to serve krabby patties seen in the episodes \"Driven to Tears\" and \"Drive Thru\" as well as ''[[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water]]''.<ref>{{cite episode |title=The Krusty Sponge |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=5 |number=89a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=10 May 2002 |credits=Writers: Paul Tibbitt, Kent Osborne, Mark O'Hare |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/feb/03/spongebob-movie-sponge-out-of-water-first-look-review |title=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water first look review \u2013 superhero slugfest drags a good sequel down |first=Jordan |last=Hoffman |date=3 February 2015 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> It is noted by Mr. Krabs that the Krusty Krab and the Krabby Patty is clean and disease-free.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Fungus Among Us |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=5 |number=83c |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=29 September  2007 |credits=Writers: Casey Alexander, Zeus Cervas, Richard Pursel |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Ingredients ==\nThe Krabby Patty is made out of a [[Frozen food|frozen]] hamburger with buns, the patty, [[pickled cucumber|pickles]], [[lettuce]], [[tomato]]es, [[cheese]],<ref>{{cite episode |title=Boss for a Day |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=12 |number=258a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=17 October 2019 |credits=Writers: Andrew Goodman |language=en}}</ref> [[ketchup]], [[Mustard (condiment)|mustard]],<ref>{{cite episode |title=Mustard O' Mine |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=11 |number=232a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=10 May 2018 |credits=Writers: Kaz |language=en}}</ref> and [[onions]]<ref>{{cite episode |title=The Way of the Sponge |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=8 |number=166b |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=25 November 2011 |credits=Writers: Casey Alexander, Zeus Cervas, Derek Iversen, Andrew Goodman |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/binging-babish-spongebob-krabby-patty/ |title=Some genius finally figured out how to make the perfect Krabby Patty |last=Rolli |first=Bryan |date=31 May 2017 |work=The Daily Dot |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and with a Krabby Patty secret formula, though said secret formula has never been revealed in the series. In the episode \"[[Just One Bite]],\" the Krusty Krab is revealed to have a \"patty vault\" that contains many Krabby Patties.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mashable.com/article/spongebob-memes-explained/ |title=Why is SpongeBob so damn meme-able? |first=Chloe |last=Bryan |work=Mashable |date=8 April 2018 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Krusty Krab's menu, the Galley Grub, consists mostly of ordinary fast food items, such as french fries and sodas. Its signature sandwich, the Krabby Patty, is celebrated, to a comic degree, by the citizens of Bikini Bottom. In ''[[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water]]'', Mr. Krabs states: \"The Krabby Patty is what ties us all together! Without it, there will be a complete breakdown of social order!\"<ref>{{cite film|title=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|title-link=The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water|type=film|date=February 6, 2015|publisher=Paramount Pictures|author=[[Paul Tibbitt|Tibbitt, Paul]] (director)|others=[[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger|Aibel, Jonathan; Berger, Glenn]] (writers)}}</ref> The sandwich comprises two buns, with the patty, lettuce, cheese, onions, tomatoes, ketchup, mustard, and pickles between them, (in that order).<ref>{{cite episode |title=Pickles |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=1 |number=6b |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=21 August 1999 |credits=[[Steven Fonti|Fonti, Steve]]; Mitchell, Chris; Burns, Peter (writers)}}</ref>\n=== Theories ===\nThe formula has been hinted at but remained a mystery throughout the series. A running gag is Plankton's obsession with obtaining it as a way to produce the sandwiches and attract customers to his across-the-street restaurant, the Chum Bucket.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2018/03/the-latest-spongebob-meme-features-the-krusty-krab-vs-chum-bucket-rivalry |title=The Latest Spongebob Meme Features the Krusty Krab vs. Chum Bucket Rivalry |last=Barner |first=Katherine |work=Complex |date=18 March 2018 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The recipe of the patty is a closely guarded [[trade secret]], which have led viewers to speculate about its contents.<ref name=\"FoodbeastMSG\">{{cite web |url=https://www.foodbeast.com/news/krabby-patty-crab-meat/ |title=People Think The Krabby Patty's Secret Was Crab Meat, And It Makes So Much Sense |last=Rocha |first=Isai |date=18 July 2017 |access-date=20 July 2019 |website=Foodbeast |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171726/https://www.foodbeast.com/news/krabby-patty-crab-meat/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"MetroPowder\">{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Sam |title=People think that the secret ingredient in SpongeBob Squarepants' Krabby Patty is cocaine |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/01/14/people-think-that-the-secret-ingredient-in-spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-is-cocaine-8343117/ |website=Metro |publisher=DMG Media |access-date=22 July  2019 |date=14 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171720/https://metro.co.uk/2019/01/14/people-think-that-the-secret-ingredient-in-spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-is-cocaine-8343117/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> Several fan theories have been formed to guess the secret ingredient.<ref name=\"SRMeat&Powder\">{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/spongebob-theory-krabby-patty-ingredients/ |title=SpongeBob Theory: What Are Krabby Patties Actually Made Of? |last=Hood |first=Cooper |date=March 16, 2019 |access-date=July 20, 2019 |website=Screen Rant |publisher=Valnet Inc. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171719/https://screenrant.com/spongebob-theory-krabby-patty-ingredients/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NewsweekPowder\">{{cite web |last1=Asarch |first1=Steven |title=Secret Ingredient In Krabby Patty? Cocaine! Says Internet |url=https://www.newsweek.com/krabby-patty-secret-ingredient-poseidon-powder-cocaine-spongebob-1294303 |website=Newsweek |access-date=22 July 2019 |date=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722171719/https://www.newsweek.com/krabby-patty-secret-ingredient-poseidon-powder-cocaine-spongebob-1294303 |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to series animator [[Vincent Waller]], \"there is absolutely no meat in the Krabby Patty. There's no animal product in there\", something which was always planned by series creator [[Stephen Hillenburg]].<ref name=\"CinemablendVegan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/1684060/whats-in-a-krabby-patty-heres-what-the-spongebob-producer-knows |title=What's In A Krabby Patty? Here's What The Spongebob Producer Knows |last=Joest |first=Mick |date=22 July 2017 |access-date=20 July 2017 |work=CinemaBlend |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725193849/http://www.cinemablend.com/television/1684060/whats-in-a-krabby-patty-heres-what-the-spongebob-producer-knows |archive-date=July 25, 2017 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> [[Mr. Lawrence]], a show writer and Plankton's voice actor, explained that the show's writers are not allowed to depict [[fish as food]]; he stated that there is no meat served in Bikini Bottom except at the Chum Bucket.<ref name=\"EliteVegan\">{{cite web |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/entertainment/spongebob-krabby-patty-theory-formula/2024695 |title=Krabby Patty Formula, According To 'Spongebob' Cast Members, Isn't What You Expected |last=Kolokathis |first=Tina |date=23 July 2017 |access-date=20 July 2019 |website=Elite Daily |publisher=Bustle Digital Group |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719085317/https://www.elitedaily.com/entertainment/spongebob-krabby-patty-theory-formula/2024695 |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> [[Tom Kenny]], the voice actor for SpongeBob, joked: \"Krabby Patties are [[hummus]]!\"<ref name=\"EliteVegan\" /> Some commentators suggest that there is actually no secret ingredient, pointing to Mr. Krabs' miserliness. A writer for [[Hollywood.com]] believes that it is \"all a ruse that crafty Mr. Krabs came up with in order to stop Plankton from focusing on [t]he Chum Bucket. It's legitimately brilliant marketing!\"<ref name=\"HollywoodPowder\">{{cite web |title=We FINALLY Know What The Krabby Patty Secret Formula Is From 'SpongeBob'! |url=http://www.hollywood.com/tv/we-finally-know-what-the-spongebob-krabby-patty-secret-formula-is-60577938/ |access-date=22 July 2019 |date=5 May 2016 |work=Hollywood.com |last=Tinubu |first=Aramide |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190615091801/http://www.hollywood.com/tv/we-finally-know-what-the-spongebob-krabby-patty-secret-formula-is-60577938/ |archive-date=15 June 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> The episode \"Patty Caper\" shows that there is truly a secret ingredient in the Krabby Patty, which is delivered to the restaurant with high security.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Patty Caper |series=SpongeBob SquarePants |season=6 |number=108a |network=Nickelodeon |airdate=5 August 2008 |credits=Writers: Casey Alexander, Zeus Cervas, Eric Shaw |language=en}}</ref> On the possibility that the secret Krabby Patty formula will be revealed in future episodes, Waller said in 2017 that he \"would not count on it\".<ref>{{cite tweet |number=881707307071033350 |user=VincentWaller72 |title=I would not count on it. |last=Waller |first=Vincent |date=2 July 2017 |access-date=28 July 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.is/eZAeW |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> In 2019, Waller stated that Hillenburg, who died in 2018, is the only person to have seen it.<ref>{{cite tweet |number=1087776914343845888 |user=VincentWaller72 |title=Yes, but no human has seen it, other than Steve. |last=Waller |first=Vincent |date=22 January 2019 |access-date=28 July 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.is/6YMGQ |archive-date=28 July 2019 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Real-life inspirations ==\nPublications such as ''[[USA Today]]'' have named it among other fictional foods that many have wanted to exist in real life,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2019/06/13/krabby-patties-butterbeer-and-more-9-fictional-foods-we-want/1442722001/ |last=Ali |first=Rasha |title=Order up: Krabby Patties, Apollo Bars and other fictional foods we wish were real |date=13 June 2019 |work=USA Today |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> but according to the ''[[New York Daily News]]'', there are four restaurants which serve a similar burger to the seen one in the show. These burgers include the Snow Crab Crispy Rice, Phuket Fantasy, Angry Crab Benedict, and Soft Shell Crab Taco.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/eats/fried-crab-spongebob-fans-article-1.2092796 |title=SpongeBob inspiring you to find your own Krabby Patty? 5 New York eateries with fresh takes on crab sandwiches |first=Gina |last=Pace |work=New York Daily News |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Krabby Patties have also inspired real life gummy confectionery treats, primarily in [[New England]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Buchanan |first1=Jesse |title=New Southington shop offers kids activities, nostalgic candy |url=http://www.myrecordjournal.com/News/Southington/Southington-News/Candy-shop-bookstore-kids-venue-opens-on-Center-Street-in-Southington.html |access-date=2 December 2019 |work=Meriden Record Journal |date=9 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Finaldi |first1=Laura |title=Finaldi: Express, Candy Barrel leaving Sarasota Square mall |url=https://www.heraldtribune.com/news/20190619/finaldi-express-candy-barrel-leaving-sarasota-square-mall |access-date=2 December 2019 |work=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=19 June 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In 2008, a doctor with [[Texas A&M Health Science Center College of Medicine]] warned parents to be aware of where the candy their child consumes is produced due to contamination then found in Chinese milk; Spongebob Gummy Krabby Patties were among those candies produced in [[China]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sigman |first1=Ashlea |title=Doctor: Be Cautious of Candy Made in China |url=https://www.kbtx.com/home/headlines/33617284.html |access-date=2 December 2019 |work=KBTX-TV |date=30 October 2008 |language=en}}</ref> In 2019, a reporter with the student newspaper of [[Capital University]] gave the gummy candies a rating of a 2 out of 10 in their review of Halloween candy.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pasco |first1=Shirleeah |title=Not all candies are created equal: Halloween candy reviews |url=http://cuchimes.com/10/2019/halloween-candy-reviews/ |access-date=2 December 2019 |work=The Chimes |date=24 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Krabby Patty has been used by [[Katy Perry]] as a second costume on the red carpet at New York's [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sea.mashable.com/entertainment/3656/katy-perry-former-chandelier-changed-into-a-hamburger-at-the-met-gala |title=Katy Perry, former chandelier, changed into a hamburger at the Met Gala |last=Lieu |first=Johnny |date=7 May 2019 |work=Mashable SEA |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In [[SpongeBob SquarePants (musical)|''The SpongeBob Musical'']], the Krabby Patty was portrayed by an actor on stage at the [[Palace Theatre, London|Palace Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/meet-krabby-patty-actor-spongebob-squarepants-musical-article-1.3666281 |title=Playing a giant Krabby Patty in 'SpongeBob SquarePants' musical can leave you feeling fried |first=Gina |last=Salamone |work=New York Daily News |date=30 November 2017 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Including various Merchandise depicting Spongebob and the Krabby Patty such as HipDot<ref>{{cite web |last=Zimmerman |first=Kelsi |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/the-hipdot-x-spongebob-collection-is-the-best-thing-since-the-invention-of-the-krabby-patty-18007378 |title=SpongeBob Is The Latest Beauty Influencer Thanks To The HipDot x SpongeBob Makeup Collection |work=Elite Daily |date=14 June 2019 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and Dog Toy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.geekalerts.com/spongebob-squarepants-krabby-patty-dog-toy/ |title=SpongeBob SquarePants Krabby Patty Dog Toy |work=Geek Alerts |first=Ryan |last=Cooper |date=3 October 2018 |access-date=2 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Krusty Krab]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{SpongeBob SquarePants}}\n\n[[Category:SpongeBob SquarePants]]\n\n[[Category:Fictional foods]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1999]]\n", "name_user": "Crywalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krabby_Patty"}
{"title_page": "Francis Norie-Miller", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n[[File:Francis_Norie-Miller.jpg|thumb|right|Norie-Miller in 1939]]\n'''Sir Francis Norie-Miller, 1st Baronet''' (11 March 1859 \u2013 4 July 1947) was a British insurance company manager director. He was also a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] and later [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|Liberal National]] politician. Although he was born in England, his chief associations were with Scotland and in particular the city of [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]]. In 1936, he was created a [[Baronet]] with the title of [[Norie-Miller Baronets|Norie-Miller of Cleeve]] in the New Year's Honours List for political and public service in the [[Perthshire|County of Perth]] <ref>''The Times'', 1 January 1936</ref> and for his local philanthropy.<ref>Robin Pearson, ''Sir Francis Norie-Miller'' in ''Dictionary of National Biography''; OUP 2004-08</ref>\n\n==Family and education==\nNorie-Miller was born at [[Cheshunt]] in [[Hertfordshire]],<ref>Pearson, DNB</ref> the son of Henry Miller, the Chief Statistical Officer for [[HM Customs]] and his wife Anne Norrie.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> Norie-Miller was educated privately and then trained for the law but he never practised and began a career in insurance instead. In 1884 he married Grace Harvey Day, the daughter of the vicar of Cheshunt. They had two sons, Claud, who was killed on active service in 1917 and Stanley who went on to succeed his father in the baronetcy and in business.<ref>Pearson, DNB</ref> They also had a daughter, Elwena.<ref>''The Times'', 30 January 1907</ref> Norie-Miller's first wife died in 1931 and three years later he married his secretary Florence Jean Belfrage McKim, of [[Scone, Scotland|Scone]] in [[Perthshire]].<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref>\n\n==Career==\nNorie-Miller began his insurance career in London, then moved to [[Glasgow]] and for practically the next sixty years he was a chief officer of a number of insurance companies. He was particularly associated with the [[General Accident, Fire and Life Assurance Association]], which he joined soon after it was incorporated in 1885. He played a crucial role in developing its business base in the United Kingdom and later was central in the company's expansion overseas, most notably in the USA. Under his dynamic direction the company built up a worldwide business.<ref>W H Marwick, ''Scotland in Modern Times: An Outline of Economic and Social Development Since the Union Of 1707''; Routledge, 1964, p119</ref> He went on to be its Chairman and Managing Director. The portrait of Norie-Miller which hung in the company board room in Perth bore the legend \"Founder of the Company\".<ref>''The Times'', Obituary; 5 July 1947</ref>  One historian of the insurance industry has described Norie-Miller as one of \u2018the great insurance autocrats of the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries\u2019.<ref>Robin Pearson, ''Insuring the Industrial Revolution: Fire Insurance in Great Britain, 1700-1850''; Ashgate Publishing, Ltd., 2004 p363</ref>\nAlthough Norie Miller based his business in Scotland it would appear that he didn't recognise Scotland as a nation. Advertising posters for his company would read Perth, N.B. i.e. North Britain.\n\n==Public service==\nNorie-Miller was intimately involved with the civic life of Perth for many years. He was a [[Justice of the Peace]] for the county of Perthshire for nearly 50 years. For over 21 years he was Chairman of the School Board of Perth or of Perth County Education Authority and he was for 32 years Director (15 years Chairman) [[Perth Royal Infirmary]].<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> In 1907 he was made an honorary fellow of the Educational Institute of Scotland <ref>Pearson, DNB</ref> and in 1933 he became a [[Freedom of the City|freeman]] of the city of Perth.<ref>''The Times'', 30 September 1933</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nNorie-Miller contested [[Perth (UK Parliament constituency)|Perth]] as a Liberal at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 general election]]. The Liberal Party, led by Sir [[Herbert Samuel, 1st Viscount Samuel|Herbert Samuel]] had agreed to support the [[National Government (United Kingdom)|National Government]] of [[Ramsay MacDonald]] at the 1931 general election, with some reservations over the traditional Liberal policy of [[free trade]] and Norie-Miller fought the election publicly supporting the government . However the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] also supported the National Government and neither party therefore had a clear advantage with the electorate in terms of identification with the National Government.\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1931 United Kingdom general election|General election 1931]]: Perth<ref>''The Times Guide to the House of Commons, 1931''; Politico's Publishing 2003 p122</ref>}}\n\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK) \n  |candidate  = [[Mungo Murray, 7th Earl of Mansfield and Mansfield|Lord Scone]]\n  |votes      = 19,254\n  |percentage = 50.2\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = '''Francis Norie-Miller'''\n  |votes      = 15,396\n  |percentage = 40.1\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Helen Gault\n  |votes      = 3,705\n  |percentage = 9.7\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 3,858\n  |percentage = \n  |change     =\n}}\n{{election box end}}\n\nNorie-Miller then stood down as prospective Liberal candidate for Perth and in 1934 the local Liberal Association selected [[James Scott (1876-1939)|James Scott]], the former Liberal MP for [[Kincardine and Aberdeenshire West (UK Parliament constituency)|Kincardine and Aberdeenshire West]] as their new representative. In 1935, when Lord Scone succeeded his father as [[Earl of Mansfield and Mansfield]] and went to the [[House of Lords]], a by-election was called for Perth. However, instead of adopting James Scott as their Parliamentary candidate, the Perth Liberals invited Norie-Miller to fight the election as they learned that Perth Conservatives were willing not to oppose him at the by-election providing he stood as a National candidate.<ref>''The Times'', 23 March 1935</ref> Scott was known as a strong supporter of Free Trade <ref>''The Times House of Commons, 1931''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2003 p.117</ref> whereas Norie-Miller favoured tariffs and protectionism.<ref>The Liberal Magazine For the Year 1935; Liberal Publication Dept.,1935 p229</ref> In a straight fight with the Labour candidate the former MP Adam McKinley, Norie-Miller won the by-election on 16 April 1935 by a majority of 9,532.\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[By-election of 16 April 1935: Perth]] <ref>''The Times'', 18 April 1935</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)\n  |candidate  = '''Francis Norie-Miller'''\n  |votes      = 17,516\n  |percentage = 68.7\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = A McKinley\n  |votes      = 7,984\n  |percentage = 31.3\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 9,532\n  |percentage = \n  |change     =\n}}\n{{election box end}}\n\nWhether Norie-Miller simply did not take to political life, or found it clashed too greatly with his business responsibilities or if he just felt he was too old at 76 to give Parliament its proper attention, he decided not to contest the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 general election]] in November that year. There had clearly been some confusion about his candidacy and its joint support by local Liberal and Conservative Associations. Shortly before the election, a Captain Harry Houldsworth, looked set to contest the seat as a National Conservative but suddenly withdrew claiming he had misunderstood the local position and in the belief that Norie-Miller wished to continue.<ref>''The Times'',  25 October 1935</ref> There was division in the Conservative ranks about whether to renew support for Norie-Miller. On 26 October, Norie-Miller did withdraw from the electoral race, citing medical reasons and the confusion of the position but the Unionists did not re-select Captain Houldsworth as their man, turning instead to [[Thomas Hunter (Scottish politician)|Thomas Hunter]], who was described in ''[[The Times]]'' newspaper as the [[Lord Provost]] of Perth and who could also rely on Liberal support. So no Liberal candidate of any stripe contested the 1935 general election in Perth which was won by the Unionists in a straight fight with Labour.<ref>''The Times House of Commons, 1935''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2003, p150</ref>\n\n==Death==\nNorie-Miller remained active in the insurance business until the time of his death, as chairman of General Accident until 1944 and as its honorary governor from 1938 until his death in 1947. He died at his home at Cleeve, Cherrybank, near Perth, on 4 July 1947, aged 88 years, and was buried at [[St Ninian's Cathedral, Perth]] where he had been a worshipper.<ref>Pearson, DNB</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of United Kingdom MPs with the shortest service]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-francis-norie-miller | Francis Norie-Miller }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Perth (UK Parliament constituency)|Perth]]\n | years  = [[1935 Perth by-election|April 1935]] \u2013 [[1935 United Kingdom general election|November 1935]]\n | before = [[Mungo Murray, 7th Earl of Mansfield and Mansfield|Lord Scone]]\n | after  = [[Thomas Hunter (Scottish politician)|Thomas Hunter]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|uk-bt}}\n{{s-new | creation }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Norie-Miller Baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''''(of Cleeve)'''''\n | years  = 1936\u20131947\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Stanley Norie-Miller]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norie-Miller, Francis}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:People from Cheshunt]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n[[File:Francis_Norie-Miller.jpg|thumb|right|Norie-Miller in 1939]]\n'''Sir Francis Norie-Miller, 1st Baronet''' (11 March 1859 \u2013 4 July 1947) was a British insurance company manager director. He was also a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] and later [[National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)|Liberal National]] politician. Although he was born in England, his chief associations were with Scotland and in particular the city of [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]]. In 1936, he was created a [[Baronet]] with the title of [[Norie-Miller Baronets|Norie-Miller of Cleeve]] in the New Year\u2019s Honours List for political and public service in the [[Perthshire|County of Perth]] <ref>''The Times'', 1 January 1936</ref> and for his local philanthropy.<ref>Robin Pearson, ''Sir Francis Norie-Miller'' in ''Dictionary of National Biography''; OUP 2004-08</ref>\n\n==Family and education==\nNorie-Miller was born at [[Cheshunt]] in [[Hertfordshire]],<ref>Pearson, DNB</ref> the son of Henry Miller, the Chief Statistical Officer for [[HM Customs]] and his wife Anne Norrie.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> Norie-Miller was educated privately and then trained for the law but he never practised and began a career in insurance instead. In 1884 he married Grace Harvey Day, the daughter of the vicar of Cheshunt. They had two sons, Claud, who was killed on active service in 1917 and Stanley who went on to succeed his father in the baronetcy and in business.<ref>Pearson, DNB</ref> They also had a daughter, Elwena.<ref>''The Times'', 30 January 1907</ref> Norie-Miller's first wife died in 1931 and three years later he married his secretary Florence Jean Belfrage McKim, of [[Scone, Scotland|Scone]] in [[Perthshire]].<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref>\n\n==Career==\nNorie-Miller began his insurance career in London, then moved to [[Glasgow]] and for practically the next sixty years he was a chief officer of a number of insurance companies. He was particularly associated with the [[General Accident, Fire and Life Assurance Association]], which he joined soon after it was incorporated in 1885. He played a crucial role in developing its business base in the United Kingdom and later was central in the company\u2019s expansion overseas, most notably in the USA. Under his dynamic direction the company built up a worldwide business.<ref>W H Marwick, ''Scotland in Modern Times: An Outline of Economic and Social Development Since the Union Of 1707''; Routledge, 1964, p119</ref> He went on to be its Chairman and Managing Director. The portrait of Norie-Miller which hung in the company board room in Perth bore the legend \"Founder of the Company\".<ref>''The Times'', Obituary; 5 July 1947</ref>  One historian of the insurance industry has described Norie-Miller as one of \u2018the great insurance autocrats of the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries\u2019.<ref>Robin Pearson, ''Insuring the Industrial Revolution: Fire Insurance in Great Britain, 1700-1850''; Ashgate Publishing, Ltd., 2004 p363</ref>\nAlthough Norie Miller based his business in Scotland it would appear that he didn't recognise Scotland as a nation. Advertising posters for his company would read Perth, N.B. i.e. North Britain.\n\n==Public service==\nNorie-Miller was intimately involved with the civic life of Perth for many years. He was a [[Justice of the Peace]] for the county of Perthshire for nearly 50 years. For over 21 years he was Chairman of the School Board of Perth or of Perth County Education Authority and he was for 32 years Director (15 years Chairman) [[Perth Royal Infirmary]].<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> In 1907 he was made an honorary fellow of the Educational Institute of Scotland <ref>Pearson, DNB</ref> and in 1933 he became a [[Freedom of the City|freeman]] of the city of Perth.<ref>''The Times'', 30 September 1933</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nNorie-Miller contested [[Perth (UK Parliament constituency)|Perth]] as a Liberal at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 general election]]. The Liberal Party, led by Sir [[Herbert Samuel, 1st Viscount Samuel|Herbert Samuel]] had agreed to support the [[National Government (United Kingdom)|National Government]] of [[Ramsay MacDonald]] at the 1931 general election, with some reservations over the traditional Liberal policy of [[free trade]] and Norie-Miller fought the election publicly supporting the government . However the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] also supported the National Government and neither party therefore had a clear advantage with the electorate in terms of identification with the National Government.\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1931 United Kingdom general election|General election 1931]]: Perth<ref>''The Times Guide to the House of Commons, 1931''; Politico's Publishing 2003 p122</ref>}}\n\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK) \n  |candidate  = [[Mungo Murray, 7th Earl of Mansfield and Mansfield|Lord Scone]]\n  |votes      = 19,254\n  |percentage = 50.2\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = '''Francis Norie-Miller'''\n  |votes      = 15,396\n  |percentage = 40.1\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Helen Gault\n  |votes      = 3,705\n  |percentage = 9.7\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 3,858\n  |percentage = \n  |change     =\n}}\n{{election box end}}\n\nNorie-Miller then stood down as prospective Liberal candidate for Perth and in 1934 the local Liberal Association selected [[James Scott (1876-1939)|James Scott]], the former Liberal MP for [[Kincardine and Aberdeenshire West (UK Parliament constituency)|Kincardine and Aberdeenshire West]] as their new representative. In 1935, when Lord Scone succeeded his father as [[Earl of Mansfield and Mansfield]] and went to the [[House of Lords]], a by-election was called for Perth. However, instead of adopting James Scott as their Parliamentary candidate, the Perth Liberals invited Norie-Miller to fight the election as they learned that Perth Conservatives were willing not to oppose him at the by-election providing he stood as a National candidate.<ref>''The Times'', 23 March 1935</ref> Scott was known as a strong supporter of Free Trade <ref>''The Times House of Commons, 1931''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2003 p.117</ref> whereas Norie-Miller favoured tariffs and protectionism.<ref>The Liberal Magazine For the Year 1935; Liberal Publication Dept.,1935 p229</ref> In a straight fight with the Labour candidate the former MP Adam McKinley, Norie-Miller won the by-election on 16 April 1935 by a majority of 9,532.\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[By-election of 16 April 1935: Perth]] <ref>''The Times'', 18 April 1935</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = National Liberal Party (UK, 1931)\n  |candidate  = '''Francis Norie-Miller'''\n  |votes      = 17,516\n  |percentage = 68.7\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = A McKinley\n  |votes      = 7,984\n  |percentage = 31.3\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 9,532\n  |percentage = \n  |change     =\n}}\n{{election box end}}\n\nWhether Norie-Miller simply did not take to political life, or found it clashed too greatly with his business responsibilities or if he just felt he was too old at 76 to give Parliament its proper attention, he decided not to contest the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 general election]] in November that year. There had clearly been some confusion about his candidacy and its joint support by local Liberal and Conservative Associations. Shortly before the election, a Captain Harry Houldsworth, looked set to contest the seat as a National Conservative but suddenly withdrew claiming he had misunderstood the local position and in the belief that Norie-Miller wished to continue.<ref>''The Times'',  25 October 1935</ref> There was division in the Conservative ranks about whether to renew support for Norie-Miller. On 26 October, Norie-Miller did withdraw from the electoral race, citing medical reasons and the confusion of the position but the Unionists did not re-select Captain Houldsworth as their man, turning instead to [[Thomas Hunter (Scottish politician)|Thomas Hunter]], who was described in ''[[The Times]]'' newspaper as the [[Lord Provost]] of Perth and who could also rely on Liberal support. So no Liberal candidate of any stripe contested the 1935 general election in Perth which was won by the Unionists in a straight fight with Labour.<ref>''The Times House of Commons, 1935''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2003, p150</ref>\n\n==Death==\nNorie-Miller remained active in the insurance business until the time of his death, as chairman of General Accident until 1944 and as its honorary governor from 1938 until his death in 1947. He died at his home at Cleeve, Cherrybank, near Perth, on 4 July 1947, aged 88 years, and was buried at [[St Ninian's Cathedral, Perth]] where he had been a worshipper.<ref>Pearson, DNB</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of United Kingdom MPs with the shortest service]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-francis-norie-miller | Francis Norie-Miller }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Perth (UK Parliament constituency)|Perth]]\n | years  = [[1935 Perth by-election|April 1935]] \u2013 [[1935 United Kingdom general election|November 1935]]\n | before = [[Mungo Murray, 7th Earl of Mansfield and Mansfield|Lord Scone]]\n | after  = [[Thomas Hunter (Scottish politician)|Thomas Hunter]]\n}}\n{{s-reg|uk-bt}}\n{{s-new | creation }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title  = [[Norie-Miller Baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''''(of Cleeve)'''''\n | years  = 1936\u20131947\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Stanley Norie-Miller]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Norie-Miller, Francis}}\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:1947 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Scottish Liberal Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:People from Cheshunt]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Norie-Miller"}
{"title_page": "King-Size Homer", "text_new": "{{Infobox Simpsons episode\n| title          = King-Size Homer\n| image          = [[File:King-Size Homer.png|225px]]\n| caption        = A grossly [[Obesity|overweight]] Homer operates his computer from the couch with a broom.\n| season         = 7\n| episode        = 7\n| director       = [[Jim Reardon]]<ref name=\"book\"/>\n| writer         = [[Dan Greaney]]<ref name=\"book\"/>\n| production     = 3F05\n| airdate        = November 5, 1995<ref name=\"book\"/>\n| guests         = [[Dr. Joan Kenley]] as the telephone lady\n| blackboard     = \"Indian burns are not our cultural heritage\"<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book |last=Groening |first=Matt |authorlink=Matt Groening |editor1-first=Ray |editor1-last=Richmond |editor1-link=Ray Richmond |editor2-first=Antonia |editor2-last=Coffman |title=[[The Simpsons episode guides#The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family|The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family]] |edition=1st |year=1997 |location=New York |publisher=[[HarperPerennial]] |lccn=98141857 |ol=433519M |oclc=37796735 |isbn=978-0-06-095252-5 |page=[https://archive.org/details/simpsonscomplete00groe/page/228 228] |ref={{harvid|Richmond & Coffman|1997}} }}.</ref>\n| couch_gag      = The Simpsons are five malfunctioning wind-up dolls who waddle their way to the couch.\n| commentary     = [[Matt Groening]]<br/>Bill Oakley<br/>Josh Weinstein<br/>Dan Greaney<br/>Jim Reardon<br/>[[David Silverman (animator)|David Silverman]]\n| prev           = [[Treehouse of Horror VI]]\n| next           = [[Mother Simpson]]\n}}\n\n\"'''King-Size Homer'''\" is the seventh episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki> [[The Simpsons (season 7)|seventh season]]. It originally aired on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox network]] in the United States on November 5, 1995. In the episode, [[Homer Simpson|Homer]] despises the [[Springfield Nuclear Power Plant|nuclear plant]]'s new exercise program and decides to gain {{convert|61|lb|kg|0}} to claim a [[disability]] and work at home.\n\nThe episode was written by [[Dan Greaney]] and directed by [[Jim Reardon]]. Joan Kenley makes her second of three guest appearances on ''The Simpsons'' in the episode as the voice of the telephone lady. It features cultural references to the [[McGuire twins|world's heaviest twins]], the 1993 film ''[[What's Eating Gilbert Grape]]'', and the soft drink [[Tab (drink)|Tab]]. \n\nSince airing, the episode has received positive reviews from fans and television critics, and ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' named it the best episode of the series. \n\nIt acquired a [[Nielsen rating]] of 10.0, and was the third highest rated show on the Fox network that week.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Mr. Burns]] organizes a morning [[calisthenics]] program at the nuclear power plant, to [[Homer Simpson|Homer]]'s dismay. After learning that an employee who is [[disability|disabled]] can work from home through [[Workers' compensation|worker's compensation]], Homer unsuccessfully tries to injure himself. Upon learning that employees who weigh {{convert|300|lb|kg|0}} or more qualify as disabled, he begins eating excessively, despite [[Marge Simpson|Marge]] and [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]]'s repeated warnings that he is endangering his health. With [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] and [[Dr Nick]]'s help, Homer gains the {{convert|61|lb|kg|0}} needed to reach 300 and Mr. Burns installs a stay-at-home work [[Computer terminal|terminal]] in the Simpson house. Marge admits that she finds herself less attracted to Homer because of his weight gain, but he vows to prove he can be a better worker because of it.\n\nHomer soon tires of his monotonous responsibilities as a safety inspector and resorts to simply typing [[Yes (Unix)|\"yes\"]] every time the system prompts him. Looking for shortcuts, he leaves his terminal with a [[drinking bird]] to press the Y key to indicate \"yes\" on the keyboard and goes to the cinema. After being denied admission due to his weight, Homer returns to find that his bird has fallen over and a [[nuclear meltdown]] is imminent unless the system is manually shut down.\n\nUnable to call the plant because his fingers are too fat to dial a telephone keypad, and too heavy to drive or skateboard, Homer resorts to hitchhiking. Drivers refuse to pick him up because his bright [[muumuu]] and excited jabbering make him seem like a lunatic. After hijacking an [[Ice cream van|ice cream truck]], Homer arrives at the power plant during a workout program and reaches the shutdown button. He falls onto the gas storage tank, blocking the release tube with the oversized lower half of his body and preventing an explosion. Grateful, Mr. Burns gives Homer a medal for bravery and offers him any request he chooses. Realizing how his obesity has made life hard for his family, Homer asks Burns to make him thin again. After a failed attempt at calisthenics, Burns agrees to pay for Homer's [[liposuction]].\n\n==Production==\n\"King-Size Homer\" was written by [[Dan Greaney]], and directed by [[Jim Reardon]]. It was the first episode Greaney wrote for ''The Simpsons''. Prior to this episode he was working as a lawyer and was contemplating moving to [[Ukraine]] to work for a start-up company. He said that this episode \"saved\" him from doing so.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> Greaney pitched some ideas to the writing staff, but none of them were satisfactory, so then-show runner [[Bill Oakley]] gave him the idea for this episode.<ref name=\"Geaney\">{{cite video |people=Greaney, Dan |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Oakley had Greaney come to [[Hollywood]] to write it, and when Greaney showed the first draft to the staff, they liked it, so Oakley hired him.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/>\n\nThe writers wanted the title of the episode to make Homer sound proud about his weight, so they decided to name it \"King-Size Homer\".<ref name=\"Oakley\">{{cite video |people=Oakley, Bill |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Greaney really enjoyed working on the episode because Homer is constantly happy and goal-oriented in it, instead of being a slob who is \"eating all the time\".<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> Animator [[David Silverman (animator)|David Silverman]] designed the obese Homer for the episode.<ref name=\"Silverman\">{{cite video |people=Silverman, David |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> There was a discussion about what Homer would wear when he became fat, and they decided to go with a [[muumuu]].<ref name=\"Oakley\"/> The writers were also discussing about how they were going to treat Homer's obesity. They did not want Homer to come off as a \"hog\", so they decided that the viewer should barely see him eating after he reaches his 300 pounds goal.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> As the writers were trying to figure out a way to get Homer back to his old weight by the end of the episode, it was suggested that Homer should feel bad about his obesity, and therefore become thin for Marge, but that idea was scrapped in early production.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> Action figurines based on obese Homer were made for the [[World of Springfield]] in December 2001.<ref name=\"Groening\">{{cite video |people=Groening, Matt |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\nHomer has a dream in which he is standing at the foot of a mountain with 300 pounds as the goal at the top. A pig wearing a tuxedo appears next to him in the dream, and motivates Homer to reach the top of the mountain. This scene was inspired by the cover of the \"Sweetness and Light\" issue of [[National Lampoon (magazine)|''National Lampoon'']] magazine.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> The staff thought that [[Cary Grant]] would have been ideal for the pig in Homer's dream sequence, but he died nine years before the episode was made, so they used cast member [[Hank Azaria]] for that voice.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> Joan Kenley guest starred in the episode as the telephone lady.<ref name=\"book\"/> The staff flew her down from [[Northern California]] to record her part for the episode.<ref name=\"Reardon\">{{cite video |people=Reardon, Jim |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nWhile Homer is in the clothes store, two [[mannequin]]s wearing similar outfits and riding on bikes are shown. These are based on [[McGuire twins|Billy and Benny McCrary]], the world's heaviest twins who weighed over {{convert|700|lb|kg|0}} each. They received fame after appearing in ''[[The Guinness Book of World Records]]'' in a picture that depicts the twins riding their [[Honda motorcycles]]. They would appear again in the same season in the episode \"[[The Day the Violence Died]]\".<ref name=\"Oakley\"/> The scene in which Bart and his friends observe the obese Homer through a window is based on a scene from the 1993 film ''[[What's Eating Gilbert Grape]]''.<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\nHomer thinks that he can order the soft drink [[Tab (drink)|Tab]] by pressing the [[tab key]] on the keyboard, and becomes anxious when he can't find the \"[[any key]]\".<ref name=\"Oakley\"/> When Homer vents gas from a nuclear reactor, the gas destroys crops of corn. A farmer says, \"Oh no, the corn! [[Paul Newman]]'s gonna have ma' legs broke!\". This is in reference to the legend of [[Newman's Own]] popcorn products, in which Newman threatened anyone who might attempt to steal his popcorn.<ref name=\"Groening\"/> At the cinema, Homer tries to watch the film ''Honk If You're Horny'', starring actor [[Pauly Shore]] and actress [[Faye Dunaway]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> When Mr. Burns awards Homer a medal at the end of the episode, he praises him for \"turning a potential [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl]] into a mere [[Three Mile Island accident|Three Mile Island]],\" referencing the real-life [[Nuclear and radiation accidents and incidents|nuclear disasters]] that occurred at those locations.\n\n==Reception==\nIn its original broadcast, \"King-Size Homer\" finished 45th (tied with ''[[Grace Under Fire]]'') in the ratings for the week of October 30 to November 3, 1995, with a [[Nielsen rating]] of 10.0.<ref name=ratings>{{cite news |title=CBS Tops In Weekend Ratings Race |date=November 10, 1995 |page=44D |work=[[Rocky Mountain News]] |author=Moore, Frazier}} Retrieved on December 6, 2008.</ref> The episode was the third highest rated show on the Fox network that week.<ref name=ratings/>\n\nSince airing, the episode has received mostly positive reviews from fans and television critics, making many top episode lists. \n\nIn 2008, ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' placed ''The Simpsons'' at the top of their list of \"The 50 Greatest TV Shows of All Time\", and noted \"King-Size Homer\" as the show's best episode, calling it \"An unimprovable mix of sharp dialogue, hilarious sight gags and heart.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/50greatesttv/default.asp?tv=1 |title=The 50 Greatest TV Shows of All Time |accessdate=2008-03-29 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]}}</ref>  \n\nKimberly Potts of [[AOL Television]] named the episode the seventh best episode of the series. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://television.aol.com/feature/the-simpsons |title='The Simpsons' Best Episodes Ever |last=Potts |first=Kimberly |publisher=AOL Television |accessdate=2008-12-06}}</ref>  \n\nMichael Moran of ''[[The Times]]'' ranked it as the tenth best.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article6988097.ece?token=null&offset=0&page=1 |title=The 10 best Simpsons episodes ever |last=Moran |first=Michael |date=January 14, 2010 |work=[[The Times]] |accessdate=2010-01-14}}</ref> \n\n\"King-Size Homer\" appeared on ''[[The Star-Ledger]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s list of the ten best episodes on ''The Simpsons'' that represent the comic and emotional scope of the show.<ref>{{cite news |title=The best of \"The Simpsons\" doing their worst |last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |date=April 26, 1998 |work=The Star-Ledger |page=5}}</ref> \n\nThe ''[[Herald Sun]]'' put the episode at ninth place on their list of the top twenty episodes of ''The Simpsons'', and highlighted the scene in which Homer is seen \"commandeering an ice cream truck in a frantic dash to the nuclear plant to avoid an impending meltdown\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simpsons Top 20 |date=April 21, 2007 |work=Herald Sun |page=W09}}</ref> \n\nEmily VanDerWerff of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' named the episode the show's fifth best, stating \"while there are a lot of funny jokes in this episode (including Homer's fingers that are too fat to dial), the best thing about it is the sight of Homer, weighing well over 300 pounds, dressed in a muumuu and a 'fat guy hat.' The climax is a little forced and cartoon-y...but Homer's weight gain works so well visually that the episode gets away with a lot more than it might.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/tv/5-for-the-day-the-simpsons/ |title=5 for the Day: The Simpsons |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |accessdate=2011-09-08 |date=2007-08-01 |author=VanDerWerff, Emily}}</ref>\n\nDave Foster of DVD Times said: \"The glee to which [Homer] takes to the challenge and the enthusiasm which Bart brings to the project show these two really do connect when the situation is oh so wrong, and the method in which the writers tackle the not-always-so-obvious downsides to such a disability are both adult and astutely amusing.\"<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=2008-12-01 |url=http://www.dvdtimes.co.uk/content.php?contentid=60554 |title=The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season |publisher=DVD Times |date=2006-02-25 |author=Foster, Dave }}</ref> \n\nJennifer Malkowski of DVD Verdict considered the best part of the episode to be during Homer's shopping trip to The Vast Waistband. The website concluded its review by giving the episode a grade of A.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-12-01 |url=http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/simpsonsseason7.php |title=The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season |publisher=DVD Verdict |date=2006-01-16 |author=Malkowski, Judge |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204055914/http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/simpsonsseason7.php |archivedate=2008-12-04 }}</ref> \n\nDVD Movie Guide's Colin Jacobson enjoyed the episode and called it \"one of the series' more cynical episodes\", and said that it \"pours on the laughs\". He continued by saying, \"It's amusing to see Homer's pursuit of obesity, and it exploits his idiocy well. It lacks the expected mushiness about the plight of fat folks, though it does make a point about sensitivity in an understated way.\"<ref name=dvdmovieguide>{{cite web |accessdate=2008-12-01 |url=http://www.dvdmg.com/simpsonsseasonseven.shtml |title=The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season (1995) |publisher=DVD Movie Guide |date=2006-01-05 |author=Jacobson, Colin }}</ref> \n\nDespite the numerous laughs at Homer's appearance from the staff of ''The Simpsons'' on the DVD [[audio commentary]] for the episode, the authors of the book ''I Can't Believe It's a Bigger and Better Updated Unofficial Simpsons Guide'', Warren Martyn and Adrian Wood, wrote: \"this isn't one of the best episodes. Homer's at his most irritating and childish here\u2014you really want Marge to beat him up.\" They added that Homer's antics with the computer, such as the scene in which he tries to find the [[any key]], and Mr. Burns running exercise classes are the highlights of the episode.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season7/page7.shtml |title=King-Size Homer |accessdate=2007-03-06 |author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |publisher=BBC |year=2000}}</ref> \n\n[[Screen Rant]] called it the best episode of the seventh season and the sixth greatest episode of ''The Simpsons''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/the-simpsons-best-episodes-ranked/|title=The Simpsons: The Best Episode In Every Season, Ranked|last=Sim|first=Bernardo|date=2019-09-22|website=Screen Rant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref> \n\nWhen ''The Simpsons'' began streaming on [[Disney+]] in 2019, former ''Simpsons'' writer and executive producer [[Bill Oakley]] named this one of the best classic Simpsons episodes to watch on the service.<ref>{{cite news |last=Katz |first=Mathew |title=The best classic Simpsons episodes on Disney+ |work=[[Digital Trends]] |language=|publisher=|date=2019-11-11 }}</ref> \n\nLater that same year, ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' ranked it number nine on its' list of top 30 ''Simpsons'' episodes.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Simpsons\u2019 Top 30 Episodes|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/12/the-simpsons-top-30-episodes/|publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=2019-12-17|accessdate=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|The_Simpsons/Season_7#King-Size_Homer|\"King-Size Homer\"}}\n{{Portal|The Simpsons}}\n*[http://www.thesimpsons.com/#/recaps/season-7_episode-7 \"King-Size Homer\"] at The Simpsons.com\n*{{tv.com episode|the-simpsons/king-size-homer-1420}}\n*{{imdb episode|0701144}}\n*{{snpp capsule|3F05}}\n\n{{The Simpsons episodes|7}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:The Simpsons (season 7) episodes]]\n[[Category:1995 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about obesity]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Simpsons episode\n| title          = King-Size Homer\n| image          = [[File:King-Size Homer.png|225px]]\n| caption        = A grossly [[Obesity|overweight]] Homer operates his computer from the couch with a broom.\n| season         = 7\n| episode        = 135\n| director       = [[Jim Reardon]]<ref name=\"book\"/>\n| writer         = [[Dan Greaney]]<ref name=\"book\"/>\n| production     = 3F05\n| airdate        = November 5, 1995<ref name=\"book\"/>\n| guests         = [[Dr. Joan Kenley]] as the telephone lady\n| blackboard     = \"Indian burns are not our cultural heritage\"<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book |last=Groening |first=Matt |authorlink=Matt Groening |editor1-first=Ray |editor1-last=Richmond |editor1-link=Ray Richmond |editor2-first=Antonia |editor2-last=Coffman |title=[[The Simpsons episode guides#The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family|The Simpsons: A Complete Guide to Our Favorite Family]] |edition=1st |year=1997 |location=New York |publisher=[[HarperPerennial]] |lccn=98141857 |ol=433519M |oclc=37796735 |isbn=978-0-06-095252-5 |page=[https://archive.org/details/simpsonscomplete00groe/page/228 228] |ref={{harvid|Richmond & Coffman|1997}} }}.</ref>\n| couch_gag      = The Simpsons are five malfunctioning wind-up dolls who waddle their way to the couch.\n| commentary     = [[Matt Groening]]<br/>Bill Oakley<br/>Josh Weinstein<br/>Dan Greaney<br/>Jim Reardon<br/>[[David Silverman (animator)|David Silverman]]\n| prev           = [[Treehouse of Horror VI]]\n| next           = [[Mother Simpson]]\n}}\n\n\"'''King-Size Homer'''\" is the seventh episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki> [[The Simpsons (season 7)|seventh season]]. It originally aired on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox network]] in the United States on November 5, 1995. In the episode, [[Homer Simpson|Homer]] despises the [[Springfield Nuclear Power Plant|nuclear plant]]'s new exercise program and decides to gain {{convert|61|lb|kg|0}} to claim a [[disability]] and work at home.\n\nThe episode was written by [[Dan Greaney]] and directed by [[Jim Reardon]]. Joan Kenley makes her second of three guest appearances on ''The Simpsons'' in the episode as the voice of the telephone lady. It features cultural references to the [[McGuire twins|world's heaviest twins]], the 1993 film ''[[What's Eating Gilbert Grape]]'', and the soft drink [[Tab (drink)|Tab]]. \n\nSince airing, the episode has received positive reviews from fans and television critics, and ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' named it the best episode of the series. \n\nIt acquired a [[Nielsen rating]] of 10.0, and was the third highest rated show on the Fox network that week.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Mr. Burns]] organizes a morning [[calisthenics]] program at the nuclear power plant, to [[Homer Simpson|Homer]]'s dismay. After learning that an employee who is [[disability|disabled]] can work from home through [[Workers' compensation|worker's compensation]], Homer unsuccessfully tries to injure himself. Upon learning that employees who weigh {{convert|300|lb|kg|0}} or more qualify as disabled, he begins eating excessively, despite [[Marge Simpson|Marge]] and [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]]'s repeated warnings that he is endangering his health. With [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] and [[Dr Nick]]'s help, Homer gains the {{convert|61|lb|kg|0}} needed to reach 300 and Mr. Burns installs a stay-at-home work [[Computer terminal|terminal]] in the Simpson house. Marge admits that she finds herself less attracted to Homer because of his weight gain, but he vows to prove he can be a better worker because of it.\n\nHomer soon tires of his monotonous responsibilities as a safety inspector and resorts to simply typing [[Yes (Unix)|\"yes\"]] every time the system prompts him. Looking for shortcuts, he leaves his terminal with a [[drinking bird]] to press the Y key to indicate \"yes\" on the keyboard and goes to the cinema. After being denied admission due to his weight, Homer returns to find that his bird has fallen over and a [[nuclear meltdown]] is imminent unless the system is manually shut down.\n\nUnable to call the plant because his fingers are too fat to dial a telephone keypad, and too heavy to drive or skateboard, Homer resorts to hitchhiking. Drivers refuse to pick him up because his bright [[muumuu]] and excited jabbering make him seem like a lunatic. After hijacking an [[Ice cream van|ice cream truck]], Homer arrives at the power plant during a workout program and reaches the shutdown button. He falls onto the gas storage tank, blocking the release tube with the oversized lower half of his body and preventing an explosion. Grateful, Mr. Burns gives Homer a medal for bravery and offers him any request he chooses. Realizing how his obesity has made life hard for his family, Homer asks Burns to make him thin again. After a failed attempt at calisthenics, Burns agrees to pay for Homer's [[liposuction]].\n\n==Production==\n\"King-Size Homer\" was written by [[Dan Greaney]], and directed by [[Jim Reardon]]. It was the first episode Greaney wrote for ''The Simpsons''. Prior to this episode he was working as a lawyer and was contemplating moving to [[Ukraine]] to work for a start-up company. He said that this episode \"saved\" him from doing so.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> Greaney pitched some ideas to the writing staff, but none of them were satisfactory, so then-show runner [[Bill Oakley]] gave him the idea for this episode.<ref name=\"Geaney\">{{cite video |people=Greaney, Dan |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Oakley had Greaney come to [[Hollywood]] to write it, and when Greaney showed the first draft to the staff, they liked it, so Oakley hired him.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/>\n\nThe writers wanted the title of the episode to make Homer sound proud about his weight, so they decided to name it \"King-Size Homer\".<ref name=\"Oakley\">{{cite video |people=Oakley, Bill |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Greaney really enjoyed working on the episode because Homer is constantly happy and goal-oriented in it, instead of being a slob who is \"eating all the time\".<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> Animator [[David Silverman (animator)|David Silverman]] designed the obese Homer for the episode.<ref name=\"Silverman\">{{cite video |people=Silverman, David |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> There was a discussion about what Homer would wear when he became fat, and they decided to go with a [[muumuu]].<ref name=\"Oakley\"/> The writers were also discussing about how they were going to treat Homer's obesity. They did not want Homer to come off as a \"hog\", so they decided that the viewer should barely see him eating after he reaches his 300 pounds goal.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> As the writers were trying to figure out a way to get Homer back to his old weight by the end of the episode, it was suggested that Homer should feel bad about his obesity, and therefore become thin for Marge, but that idea was scrapped in early production.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> Action figurines based on obese Homer were made for the [[World of Springfield]] in December 2001.<ref name=\"Groening\">{{cite video |people=Groening, Matt |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\nHomer has a dream in which he is standing at the foot of a mountain with 300 pounds as the goal at the top. A pig wearing a tuxedo appears next to him in the dream, and motivates Homer to reach the top of the mountain. This scene was inspired by the cover of the \"Sweetness and Light\" issue of [[National Lampoon (magazine)|''National Lampoon'']] magazine.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> The staff thought that [[Cary Grant]] would have been ideal for the pig in Homer's dream sequence, but he died nine years before the episode was made, so they used cast member [[Hank Azaria]] for that voice.<ref name=\"Geaney\"/> Joan Kenley guest starred in the episode as the telephone lady.<ref name=\"book\"/> The staff flew her down from [[Northern California]] to record her part for the episode.<ref name=\"Reardon\">{{cite video |people=Reardon, Jim |date=2005 |title=The Simpsons season 7 DVD commentary for the episode \"King-Size Homer\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nWhile Homer is in the clothes store, two [[mannequin]]s wearing similar outfits and riding on bikes are shown. These are based on [[McGuire twins|Billy and Benny McCrary]], the world's heaviest twins who weighed over {{convert|700|lb|kg|0}} each. They received fame after appearing in ''[[The Guinness Book of World Records]]'' in a picture that depicts the twins riding their [[Honda motorcycles]]. They would appear again in the same season in the episode \"[[The Day the Violence Died]]\".<ref name=\"Oakley\"/> The scene in which Bart and his friends observe the obese Homer through a window is based on a scene from the 1993 film ''[[What's Eating Gilbert Grape]]''.<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\nHomer thinks that he can order the soft drink [[Tab (drink)|Tab]] by pressing the [[tab key]] on the keyboard, and becomes anxious when he can't find the \"[[any key]]\".<ref name=\"Oakley\"/> When Homer vents gas from a nuclear reactor, the gas destroys crops of corn. A farmer says, \"Oh no, the corn! [[Paul Newman]]'s gonna have ma' legs broke!\". This is in reference to the legend of [[Newman's Own]] popcorn products, in which Newman threatened anyone who might attempt to steal his popcorn.<ref name=\"Groening\"/> At the cinema, Homer tries to watch the film ''Honk If You're Horny'', starring actor [[Pauly Shore]] and actress [[Faye Dunaway]].<ref name=\"BBC\"/> When Mr. Burns awards Homer a medal at the end of the episode, he praises him for \"turning a potential [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl]] into a mere [[Three Mile Island accident|Three Mile Island]],\" referencing the real-life [[Nuclear and radiation accidents and incidents|nuclear disasters]] that occurred at those locations.\n\n==Reception==\nIn its original broadcast, \"King-Size Homer\" finished 45th (tied with ''[[Grace Under Fire]]'') in the ratings for the week of October 30 to November 3, 1995, with a [[Nielsen rating]] of 10.0.<ref name=ratings>{{cite news |title=CBS Tops In Weekend Ratings Race |date=November 10, 1995 |page=44D |work=[[Rocky Mountain News]] |author=Moore, Frazier}} Retrieved on December 6, 2008.</ref> The episode was the third highest rated show on the Fox network that week.<ref name=ratings/>\n\nSince airing, the episode has received mostly positive reviews from fans and television critics, making many top episode lists. \n\nIn 2008, ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' placed ''The Simpsons'' at the top of their list of \"The 50 Greatest TV Shows of All Time\", and noted \"King-Size Homer\" as the show's best episode, calling it \"An unimprovable mix of sharp dialogue, hilarious sight gags and heart.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/50greatesttv/default.asp?tv=1 |title=The 50 Greatest TV Shows of All Time |accessdate=2008-03-29 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]}}</ref>  \n\nKimberly Potts of [[AOL Television]] named the episode the seventh best episode of the series. <ref>{{cite web |url=http://television.aol.com/feature/the-simpsons |title='The Simpsons' Best Episodes Ever |last=Potts |first=Kimberly |publisher=AOL Television |accessdate=2008-12-06}}</ref>  \n\nMichael Moran of ''[[The Times]]'' ranked it as the tenth best.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article6988097.ece?token=null&offset=0&page=1 |title=The 10 best Simpsons episodes ever |last=Moran |first=Michael |date=January 14, 2010 |work=[[The Times]] |accessdate=2010-01-14}}</ref> \n\n\"King-Size Homer\" appeared on ''[[The Star-Ledger]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s list of the ten best episodes on ''The Simpsons'' that represent the comic and emotional scope of the show.<ref>{{cite news |title=The best of \"The Simpsons\" doing their worst |last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |date=April 26, 1998 |work=The Star-Ledger |page=5}}</ref> \n\nThe ''[[Herald Sun]]'' put the episode at ninth place on their list of the top twenty episodes of ''The Simpsons'', and highlighted the scene in which Homer is seen \"commandeering an ice cream truck in a frantic dash to the nuclear plant to avoid an impending meltdown\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Simpsons Top 20 |date=April 21, 2007 |work=Herald Sun |page=W09}}</ref> \n\nEmily VanDerWerff of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' named the episode the show's fifth best, stating \"while there are a lot of funny jokes in this episode (including Homer's fingers that are too fat to dial), the best thing about it is the sight of Homer, weighing well over 300 pounds, dressed in a muumuu and a 'fat guy hat.' The climax is a little forced and cartoon-y...but Homer's weight gain works so well visually that the episode gets away with a lot more than it might.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/tv/5-for-the-day-the-simpsons/ |title=5 for the Day: The Simpsons |work=[[Slant Magazine]] |accessdate=2011-09-08 |date=2007-08-01 |author=VanDerWerff, Emily}}</ref>\n\nDave Foster of DVD Times said: \"The glee to which [Homer] takes to the challenge and the enthusiasm which Bart brings to the project show these two really do connect when the situation is oh so wrong, and the method in which the writers tackle the not-always-so-obvious downsides to such a disability are both adult and astutely amusing.\"<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=2008-12-01 |url=http://www.dvdtimes.co.uk/content.php?contentid=60554 |title=The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season |publisher=DVD Times |date=2006-02-25 |author=Foster, Dave }}</ref> \n\nJennifer Malkowski of DVD Verdict considered the best part of the episode to be during Homer's shopping trip to The Vast Waistband. The website concluded its review by giving the episode a grade of A.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-12-01 |url=http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/simpsonsseason7.php |title=The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season |publisher=DVD Verdict |date=2006-01-16 |author=Malkowski, Judge |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204055914/http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/simpsonsseason7.php |archivedate=2008-12-04 }}</ref> \n\nDVD Movie Guide's Colin Jacobson enjoyed the episode and called it \"one of the series' more cynical episodes\", and said that it \"pours on the laughs\". He continued by saying, \"It's amusing to see Homer's pursuit of obesity, and it exploits his idiocy well. It lacks the expected mushiness about the plight of fat folks, though it does make a point about sensitivity in an understated way.\"<ref name=dvdmovieguide>{{cite web |accessdate=2008-12-01 |url=http://www.dvdmg.com/simpsonsseasonseven.shtml |title=The Simpsons: The Complete Seventh Season (1995) |publisher=DVD Movie Guide |date=2006-01-05 |author=Jacobson, Colin }}</ref> \n\nDespite the numerous laughs at Homer's appearance from the staff of ''The Simpsons'' on the DVD [[audio commentary]] for the episode, the authors of the book ''I Can't Believe It's a Bigger and Better Updated Unofficial Simpsons Guide'', Warren Martyn and Adrian Wood, wrote: \"this isn't one of the best episodes. Homer's at his most irritating and childish here\u2014you really want Marge to beat him up.\" They added that Homer's antics with the computer, such as the scene in which he tries to find the [[any key]], and Mr. Burns running exercise classes are the highlights of the episode.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season7/page7.shtml |title=King-Size Homer |accessdate=2007-03-06 |author1=Martyn, Warren |author2=Wood, Adrian |publisher=BBC |year=2000}}</ref> \n\n[[Screen Rant]] called it the best episode of the seventh season and the sixth greatest episode of ''The Simpsons''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/the-simpsons-best-episodes-ranked/|title=The Simpsons: The Best Episode In Every Season, Ranked|last=Sim|first=Bernardo|date=2019-09-22|website=Screen Rant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref> \n\nWhen ''The Simpsons'' began streaming on [[Disney+]] in 2019, former ''Simpsons'' writer and executive producer [[Bill Oakley]] named this one of the best classic Simpsons episodes to watch on the service.<ref>{{cite news |last=Katz |first=Mathew |title=The best classic Simpsons episodes on Disney+ |work=[[Digital Trends]] |language=|publisher=|date=2019-11-11 }}</ref> \n\nLater that same year, ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' ranked it number nine on its' list of top 30 ''Simpsons'' episodes.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Simpsons\u2019 Top 30 Episodes|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/12/the-simpsons-top-30-episodes/|publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=2019-12-17|accessdate=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|The_Simpsons/Season_7#King-Size_Homer|\"King-Size Homer\"}}\n{{Portal|The Simpsons}}\n*[http://www.thesimpsons.com/#/recaps/season-7_episode-7 \"King-Size Homer\"] at The Simpsons.com\n*{{tv.com episode|the-simpsons/king-size-homer-1420}}\n*{{imdb episode|0701144}}\n*{{snpp capsule|3F05}}\n\n{{The Simpsons episodes|7}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:The Simpsons (season 7) episodes]]\n[[Category:1995 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about obesity]]\n", "name_user": "Williamnilly", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King-Size_Homer"}
{"title_page": "Yes Bank", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Indian bank}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Yes Bank Limited\n| logo = Yes_Bank_logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{BSE|532648}}<br>{{NSE|YESBANK}}\n| industry = [[Banking]], [[financial service]]s<ref name=\"agm2018\">{{cite book |title=Annual Report  2017\u201318 |publisher=Yes Bank Limited |location=Mumbai |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/annualreport_2017_18_pdf |accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n| founded = {{start date and age|df=y|2004}}\n| founder = [[Rana Kapoor]]<br>Ashok Kapur<ref name=\"Ashok Kapur\">{{cite news|title=Late Ashok Kapur |publisher=|date=28 Nov 2008}}</ref>\n| key_people = Prashant Kumar <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/companies/news/prashant-kumar-to-be-ceo-md-of-yes-bank/amp-11584365766418.html|title=Prashant Kumar to be CEO & MD of Yes Bank|publisher=[[livemint]]|date=2020-03-16|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n<br>{{small|[[Managing director|MD]] & [[CEO]]}}\n| products = [[Credit card]]s, [[Retail banking|consumer banking]], [[Commercial bank|corporate banking]], [[Financial services|finance and insurance]], [[mortgage loan]]s, [[private banking]], [[wealth management]], [[investment banking]]\n| revenue = {{increase}}{{INRConvert|254.91|b|lk=r}} (2018)<ref name=\"BalSheet\">[https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/annualreport_2017_18_pdf \"Balance Sheet 31.03.2018\"] yesbank.in (17 March 2018).</ref>\n| operating_income = {{increase}}{{INRConvert|619.4|b}} (2018)<ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| net_income = {{decrease}}{{INRConvert|-15.0664|b}} (2019)<ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| assets = {{increase}}{{INRConvert|3.014|t}} (2018)<ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| equity = \n| parent = {{Unbulleted list|[[State Bank of India]] (49%)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theprint.in/economy/sbi-gets-approval-to-invest-rs-7250-crore-in-crisis-hit-yes-bank/379970/|title=SBI gets approval to invest Rs 7,250 crore in crisis-hit Yes Bank|publisher=[[The Print]]|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>|[[Life Insurance Corporation]] (10%)}}\n| num_employees = 18,239 (2018)<ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| ratio = 17.0% <ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| location = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| homepage = {{url|https://www.yesbank.in}}\n}}\n\n'''Yes Bank Limited''' is an Indian public [[bank]] headquartered in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/q1fy2019_20_press_release_cr_pdf|title=Press Release \u2013 Yes Bank }}</ref> and was founded by [[Rana Kapoor]] and Ashok Kapur in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/stocks/marketinfo/totassets/bse/banks-private-sector.html|title= Stocks in India by Net Sales, List of Top Banks \u2013 Private Sector Stocks in India (2017) \u2013 BSE|website=Moneycontrol.com|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> It offers wide range of banking and financial products for corporate and retail customers through [[retail banking]] and [[asset management]] services.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yes Bank board to meet Tuesday after RBI directive on Rana Kapoor\u2019s tenure |url=https://www.livemint.com/Industry/EUp3Jqqaj7nAoKQ9cBpoyI/Yes-Bank-board-to-meet-Tuesday-after-RBI-directive-on-Rana-K.html |accessdate=29 September 2018 |agency=PTI |publisher=Live Mint |date=24 September 2018}}</ref> On 5 March 2020, the [[Reserve Bank of India]] (RBI) has taken control of the bank which had an excessive amount of bad loans in an attempt to avoid the collapse of the bank, later reconstructed the board and named Prashant Kumar former Chief financial officer of [[State Bank of India|SBI]] as new [[Managing director|MD]] & [[CEO]] at Yes bank.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/amphtml/yes-bank-board-reconstituted-appointment-8-members-151648072.html|title=Yes Bank board reconstituted with appointment of 8 members|publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]|date=2020-03-26|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Business==\nYes Bank has interests in [[syndicated loans]] and [[corporate banking]]. It has three subsidiaries \u2013 Yes Bank, Yes Capital and Yes Asset Management Services.<ref>{{cite web |title=Investors conference call transcript |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/earnings_concall_transcript_pdf |website=Official transcript |publisher=Yes bank |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> \n\nAs of September 2018, Yes bank had taken [[syndicated loans]] from eight large international entities including [[Asian Development Bank|ADB]], [[Overseas Private Investment Corporation|OPIC]], [[European Investment Bank|European investment bank]], banks in [[Taiwan]] and [[Japan]] for amounts ranging from US$30 million to US$410 million, which it in turn lend to small and medium scale enterprises as well as large corporates. It has also both taken as well as given short term loans to a number of retail and corporate banks in Taiwan, Japan, the [[United States]], and [[Europe]].<ref>{{cite web |title=OPIC Signs Loan Agreement with Yes Bank to Support Small Business Growth in India |url=https://www.opic.gov/press-releases/2015/opic-signs-loan-agreement-yes-bank-support-small-business-growth-india |website=Press release |publisher=OPIC |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Investor presentaiton 2018\u201319 |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/yes_bank_investors_ppt_q1fy18_19_inr |website=www.yesbank.in |publisher=Yes Bank|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> It has partnered with the US government based OPIC and with [[Wells Fargo]] to support women entrepreneurs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yes Bank partners with OPIC and Wells Fargo to Support Financing of Women Entrepreneurs and SMEs |url=https://www.yesbank.in/media/press-releases/yes-bank-partners-with-opic-and-wells-fargo-to-support-financing-of-women-entrepreneurs-and-smes |website=OPIC press release |publisher=OPIC |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nYes Bank provides [[Unified Payments Interface]] (UPI) services for a number of major companies, such as [[Airtel]], [[Cleartrip]], [[RedBus.in|RedBus]], and [[PhonePe]] among others. In January 2020, it was responsible for handling 514 million UPI transactions out of the 1.31 billion made that month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/business/2020/mar/06/yes-banks-turmoil-leads-to-chaos-in-digital-payments-world-2113206.html|title=Yes Bank's turmoil leads to chaos in digital payments world|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Listings==\nYes Bank has equities listed on the [[Bombay Stock Exchange]] and the [[National Stock Exchange of India]] and has bonds listed on [[London stock exchange]]. Yes Bank was listed in the stock exchanges of India post its IPO in May 2005 at an issue price of {{INR|45}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/yes-bank-ltd/ipos/companyid-16552.cms|title=YES Bank IPO: Offer & Issue Details - The Economic Times|website=Economictimes.indiatimes.com|accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Shareholding pattern==\nAs of March 2018, as per its annual shareholders report, the three largest shareholders of Yes Bank limited were foreign portfolio investors (43%), insurance companies (14%), and mutual funds including UTI (10%).<ref>{{cite web |title=Investor presentation 2018 |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/yes_bank_investors_ppt_q1fy18_19_inr |website=Yes Bank official website |publisher=Yes Bank |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmaller (less than 5%) shareholdings were owned by its three promoters [Rana Kapoor (4%), Yes Capital (India) Pvt. Ltd. (3%), and Morgan Credits Pvt. Ltd. (3%)] and other investors including Madhu Kapur (8%), Mags Finvest Pvt. Ltd. (2%), and [[LIC India]] under its various schemes (10%). <ref>{{cite web |title=Share holding pattern as on 30 June 2018 |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/shareholding_pattern_as_on_june_30_2018 |website=official website |publisher=Yes Bank |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\nYes Bank limited operates under three distinct entities \u2013 Yes Bank, Yes Capital and Yes Asset Management.<ref>{{cite book |title=Annual shareholder report 2017-18 |publisher=Yes Bank |location=Mumbai |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/annualreport_2017_18_pdf |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2020, [[State Bank of India]] invested Rs 7,250 crore in the bank amid financial crisis and remains 49% stake capital owner of Yes Bank.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/sbi-to-buy-yes-bank-shares-worth-rs-725-crore-at-rs-10-apiece/articleshow/74593789.cms|title=SBI to buy YES Bank shares worth Rs 7,250 crore at Rs 10 apiece|publisher=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Recent developments==\nIn September 2016, Yes Bank scrapped its proposed $1 billion share sale due to market conditions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/yes-bank-says-no-to-share-sale-after-scrip-tanks/articleshow/54190552.cms|title=Yes Bank says no to share sale after scrip tanks|date=9 September 2016|publisher=|accessdate=14 October 2017|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/yes-banks-opportunism-is-to-blame-for-failed-share-sale/articleshow/54253558.cms|title=Yes Bank's opportunism is to blame for failed share sale|date=10 September 2016|publisher=|accessdate=14 October 2017|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref> The company subsequently attempted to relaunch its failed capital raising exercise after appointing a new set of bankers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/finance/yes-bank-may-appoint-new-i-banks-for-qip-116102000742_1.html|title=Yes Bank may appoint new i-banks for QIP|first=Samie Modak & Nupur|last=Anand|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=14 October 2017|publisher=[[Business Standard]]}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, the bank launched a [[digital wallet]] known as Yes Pay, integrating with [[BHIM]] and UPI.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/money/yes-bank-bhim-yes-pay-wallet-unveiled-indiastack-apis-and-npci-products-now-integrated-see-how-you-benefit/912484/|title=Yes Bank Bhim Yes Pay wallet unveiled; IndiaStack APIs and NPCI products now integrated, see how you benefit|date=2017-10-30|work=The Financial Express|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en-US}}</ref> On 3 November 2017, Yes Bank signed a [[MoU]] with the [[Government of India|government]] to provide {{INRConvert|10|b}} financing for food processing projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/yes-bank-signs-mou-with-govt-for-rs-1000-cr-financing/articleshow/61485872.cms|title=Yes Bank signs MoU with govt for Rs 1,000 cr financing|date=3 November 2017|publisher=|accessdate=11 April 2018|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 moratorium ===\nOn 5 March 2020, the [[Reserve Bank of India]] (RBI) announced that, in the interest of its customers and depositors, it would suspend and supersede Yes Bank's board and impose a 30-day moratorium on its operations. The RBI cited Yes Bank's failures to raise new funding to cover its [[Non-performing loan|non-performing assets]], inaccurate statements of confidence in its ability to receive new funding, and its underreporting of its non-performing assets, among other factors, as the impetus for this moratorium. Customers are being limited from withdrawing more than {{INRConvert|50|k}} from their accounts, except in certain exceptional circumstances (such as to cover medical care, emergencies, higher education, and \"obligatory expenses\" for ceremonies such as weddings). RBI governor [[Shaktikanta Das]] stated that the matter would be resolved \"swiftly\"; [[Minister of Finance (India)|Finance Minister]] [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] announced a proposed turnaround plan, under which the [[State Bank of India]] would take a 49% stake in Yes Bank and introduce a new board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/yes-bank-crisis-rbi-sbi-invest-withdrawal-limit-reason-full-roundup-developments-1653193-2020-03-06|title=Yes Bank crisis: From what happens to my money to will SBI be saviour, all that has happened|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/business/2020/mar/06/here-is-all-you-need-to-know-about-the-yes-bank-moratorium-2113138.html|title=Here is all you need to know about the Yes Bank moratorium|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/yes-bank-withdrawal-limit-capped-at-rs-50000/articleshow/74498382.cms|title=Yes Bank withdrawal limit capped at Rs 50,000; RBI supersedes board|date=2020-03-06|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/yes-bank-withdrawal-limit-exceptions-1653068-2020-03-06|title=Yes Bank withdrawals capped at Rs 50,000. Do these exceptions apply to you?|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March 2020, [[ICRA Limited|ICRA]] downgraded the [[Bond credit rating|rating]] of Yes Bank's {{INRConvert|526|b}} in core bonds to a \"D\" rating, while [[Moody's]] downgraded them to \"Caa3\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/moodys-lowers-yes-bank-rating-to-caa3-from-b2/articleshow/74516990.cms|title=Moody\u2019s lowers YES Bank rating to \u2018Caa3\u2019 from \u2018B2\u2019|date=2020-03-06|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/icra-downgrades-yes-banks-rs-52600-crore-bonds-to-default/articleshow/74514255.cms|title=Icra downgrades YES Bank\u2019s Rs 52,600 crore bonds to \u2018default\u2019|date=2020-03-06|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> On 8 March 2020, Yes Bank founder Rana Kapoor was arrested by the [[Enforcement Directorate]] under charges of [[money laundering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/companies/yes-bank-founder-rana-kapoor-arrested-by-ed-in-money-laundering-case-2268416.html|title=Yes Bank founder Rana Kapoor arrested by ED in money laundering case|date=2020-03-08|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\nThe moratorium has caused major disruptions to e-commerce in India, due to a number of prominent services and online stores having used Yes Bank as its payment provider for UPI. Some services using Yes Bank in tandem with other payment providers have seen fewer disruptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2020/03/06/indias-yes-bank-breakdown-disrupts-walmarts-phonepe-among-a-dozen-other-services/|title=India\u2019s Yes Bank breakdown disrupts Walmart\u2019s PhonePe among a dozen other services|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2020, the Union Cabinet approved the reconstruction scheme for Yes Bank and that within three days of the notification of the scheme the moratorium would be lifted. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/cabinet-approves-reconstruction-scheme-for-yes-bank-fm-sitharaman-5030711.html|title=Cabinet approves reconstruction scheme for Yes Bank: FM Sitharaman|website=Moneycontrol|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> During this reconstruction, seven investors infused 12000 crore in Yes bank and Prashant Kumar has been proposed as new CEO of the bank. These investors include [[State Bank of India]], [[ICICI Bank]], [[HDFC Bank]], [[Axis Bank]], [[Kotak Mahindra Bank]], [[Rakesh Jhunjhunwala]], Radhakishan Damani and Azim Premji trust. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Shukla|first=Saloni|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/seven-investors-join-sbi-to-put-over-rs-12000-cr-into-yes-bank-prashant-kumar-proposed-as-new-ceo/articleshow/74603685.cms|title=Seven investors join SBI to put over Rs 12,000 cr into Yes Bank; Prashant Kumar proposed as new CEO|date=2020-03-13|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-13|last2=Rebello|first2=Joel}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Banking in India]]\n* [[List of banks in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.yesbank.in/ Official Website]\n* [http://www.bseindia.com/stock-share-price/yes-bank-ltd/yes-bank/532648/ YES BANK] at [[Bombay Stock Exchange]]\n* [http://www.nseindia.com/live_market/dynaContent/live_watch/get_quote/GetQuote.jsp?symbol=YESBANK  BANK] at [[National Stock Exchange of India]]\n\n{{Banking in India}}\n\n[[Category:Private Sector Banks in India]]\n[[Category:Banks based in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Bombay Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:2005 initial public offerings]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Indian bank}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Yes Bank Limited\n| logo = Yes_Bank_logo.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{BSE|532648}}<br>{{NSE|YESBANK}}\n| industry = [[Banking]], [[financial service]]s<ref name=\"agm2018\">{{cite book |title=Annual Report  2017\u201318 |publisher=Yes Bank Limited |location=Mumbai |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/annualreport_2017_18_pdf |accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n| founded = {{start date and age|df=y|2004}}\n| founder = [[Rana Kapoor]]<br>Ashok Kapur<ref name=\"Ashok Kapur\">{{cite news|title=Late Ashok Kapur |publisher=|date=28 Nov 2008}}</ref>\n| key_people = Prashant Kumar <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/companies/news/prashant-kumar-to-be-ceo-md-of-yes-bank/amp-11584365766418.html|title=Prashant Kumar to be CEO & MD of Yes Bank|publisher=[[livemint]]|date=2020-03-16|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n<br>{{small|[[MD]] & [[CEO]]}}\n| products = [[Credit card]]s, [[Retail banking|consumer banking]], [[Commercial bank|corporate banking]], [[Financial services|finance and insurance]], [[mortgage loan]]s, [[private banking]], [[wealth management]], [[investment banking]]\n| revenue = {{increase}}{{INRConvert|254.91|b|lk=r}} (2018)<ref name=\"BalSheet\">[https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/annualreport_2017_18_pdf \"Balance Sheet 31.03.2018\"] yesbank.in (17 March 2018).</ref>\n| operating_income = {{increase}}{{INRConvert|619.4|b}} (2018)<ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| net_income = {{decrease}}{{INRConvert|-15.0664|b}} (2019)<ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| assets = {{increase}}{{INRConvert|3.014|t}} (2018)<ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| equity = \n| parent = {{Unbulleted list|[[State Bank of India]] (49%)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theprint.in/economy/sbi-gets-approval-to-invest-rs-7250-crore-in-crisis-hit-yes-bank/379970/|title=SBI gets approval to invest Rs 7,250 crore in crisis-hit Yes Bank|publisher=[[The Print]]|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>|[[Life Insurance Corporation]] (10%)}}\n| num_employees = 18,239 (2018)<ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| ratio = 17.0% <ref name=\"BalSheet\"/>\n| location = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| homepage = {{url|https://www.yesbank.in}}\n}}\n\n'''Yes Bank Limited''' is an Indian public [[bank]] headquartered in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/q1fy2019_20_press_release_cr_pdf|title=Press Release \u2013 Yes Bank }}</ref> and was founded by [[Rana Kapoor]] and Ashok Kapur in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/stocks/marketinfo/totassets/bse/banks-private-sector.html|title= Stocks in India by Net Sales, List of Top Banks \u2013 Private Sector Stocks in India (2017) \u2013 BSE|website=Moneycontrol.com|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> It offers wide range of banking and financial products for corporate and retail customers through [[retail banking]] and [[asset management]] services.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yes Bank board to meet Tuesday after RBI directive on Rana Kapoor\u2019s tenure |url=https://www.livemint.com/Industry/EUp3Jqqaj7nAoKQ9cBpoyI/Yes-Bank-board-to-meet-Tuesday-after-RBI-directive-on-Rana-K.html |accessdate=29 September 2018 |agency=PTI |publisher=Live Mint |date=24 September 2018}}</ref> On 5 March 2020, the [[Reserve Bank of India]] (RBI) has taken control of the bank which had an excessive amount of bad loans in an attempt to avoid the collapse of the bank, later reconstructed the board and named Prashant Kumar former Chief financial officer of [[SBI]] as new [[MD]] & [[CEO]] at Yes bank.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/amphtml/yes-bank-board-reconstituted-appointment-8-members-151648072.html|title=Yes Bank board reconstituted with appointment of 8 members|publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]|date=2020-03-26|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Business==\nYes Bank has interests in [[syndicated loans]] and [[corporate banking]]. It has three subsidiaries \u2013 Yes Bank, Yes Capital and Yes Asset Management Services.<ref>{{cite web |title=Investors conference call transcript |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/earnings_concall_transcript_pdf |website=Official transcript |publisher=Yes bank |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> \n\nAs of September 2018, Yes bank had taken [[syndicated loans]] from eight large international entities including [[Asian Development Bank|ADB]], [[Overseas Private Investment Corporation|OPIC]], [[European Investment Bank|European investment bank]], banks in [[Taiwan]] and [[Japan]] for amounts ranging from US$30 million to US$410 million, which it in turn lend to small and medium scale enterprises as well as large corporates. It has also both taken as well as given short term loans to a number of retail and corporate banks in Taiwan, Japan, the [[United States]], and [[Europe]].<ref>{{cite web |title=OPIC Signs Loan Agreement with Yes Bank to Support Small Business Growth in India |url=https://www.opic.gov/press-releases/2015/opic-signs-loan-agreement-yes-bank-support-small-business-growth-india |website=Press release |publisher=OPIC |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Investor presentaiton 2018\u201319 |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/yes_bank_investors_ppt_q1fy18_19_inr |website=www.yesbank.in |publisher=Yes Bank|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> It has partnered with the US government based OPIC and with [[Wells Fargo]] to support women entrepreneurs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Yes Bank partners with OPIC and Wells Fargo to Support Financing of Women Entrepreneurs and SMEs |url=https://www.yesbank.in/media/press-releases/yes-bank-partners-with-opic-and-wells-fargo-to-support-financing-of-women-entrepreneurs-and-smes |website=OPIC press release |publisher=OPIC |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nYes Bank provides [[Unified Payments Interface]] (UPI) services for a number of major companies, such as [[Airtel]], [[Cleartrip]], [[RedBus.in|RedBus]], and [[PhonePe]] among others. In January 2020, it was responsible for handling 514 million UPI transactions out of the 1.31 billion made that month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/business/2020/mar/06/yes-banks-turmoil-leads-to-chaos-in-digital-payments-world-2113206.html|title=Yes Bank's turmoil leads to chaos in digital payments world|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Listings==\nYes Bank has equities listed on the [[Bombay Stock Exchange]] and the [[National Stock Exchange of India]] and has bonds listed on [[London stock exchange]]. Yes Bank was listed in the stock exchanges of India post its IPO in May 2005 at an issue price of {{INR|45}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/yes-bank-ltd/ipos/companyid-16552.cms|title=YES Bank IPO: Offer & Issue Details - The Economic Times|website=Economictimes.indiatimes.com|accessdate=14 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Shareholding pattern==\nAs of March 2018, as per its annual shareholders report, the three largest shareholders of Yes Bank limited were foreign portfolio investors (43%), insurance companies (14%), and mutual funds including UTI (10%).<ref>{{cite web |title=Investor presentation 2018 |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/yes_bank_investors_ppt_q1fy18_19_inr |website=Yes Bank official website |publisher=Yes Bank |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmaller (less than 5%) shareholdings were owned by its three promoters [Rana Kapoor (4%), Yes Capital (India) Pvt. Ltd. (3%), and Morgan Credits Pvt. Ltd. (3%)] and other investors including Madhu Kapur (8%), Mags Finvest Pvt. Ltd. (2%), and [[LIC India]] under its various schemes (10%). <ref>{{cite web |title=Share holding pattern as on 30 June 2018 |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/shareholding_pattern_as_on_june_30_2018 |website=official website |publisher=Yes Bank |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\nYes Bank limited operates under three distinct entities \u2013 Yes Bank, Yes Capital and Yes Asset Management.<ref>{{cite book |title=Annual shareholder report 2017-18 |publisher=Yes Bank |location=Mumbai |url=https://www.yesbank.in/pdf/annualreport_2017_18_pdf |accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2020, [[State Bank of India]] invested Rs 7,250 crore in the bank amid financial crisis and remains 49% stake capital owner of Yes Bank.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/sbi-to-buy-yes-bank-shares-worth-rs-725-crore-at-rs-10-apiece/articleshow/74593789.cms|title=SBI to buy YES Bank shares worth Rs 7,250 crore at Rs 10 apiece|publisher=[[The Economic Times]]|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Recent developments==\nIn September 2016, Yes Bank scrapped its proposed $1 billion share sale due to market conditions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/yes-bank-says-no-to-share-sale-after-scrip-tanks/articleshow/54190552.cms|title=Yes Bank says no to share sale after scrip tanks|date=9 September 2016|publisher=|accessdate=14 October 2017|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/yes-banks-opportunism-is-to-blame-for-failed-share-sale/articleshow/54253558.cms|title=Yes Bank's opportunism is to blame for failed share sale|date=10 September 2016|publisher=|accessdate=14 October 2017|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref> The company subsequently attempted to relaunch its failed capital raising exercise after appointing a new set of bankers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/finance/yes-bank-may-appoint-new-i-banks-for-qip-116102000742_1.html|title=Yes Bank may appoint new i-banks for QIP|first=Samie Modak & Nupur|last=Anand|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=14 October 2017|publisher=[[Business Standard]]}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, the bank launched a [[digital wallet]] known as Yes Pay, integrating with [[BHIM]] and UPI.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/money/yes-bank-bhim-yes-pay-wallet-unveiled-indiastack-apis-and-npci-products-now-integrated-see-how-you-benefit/912484/|title=Yes Bank Bhim Yes Pay wallet unveiled; IndiaStack APIs and NPCI products now integrated, see how you benefit|date=2017-10-30|work=The Financial Express|access-date=2018-04-11|language=en-US}}</ref> On 3 November 2017, Yes Bank signed a [[MoU]] with the [[Government of India|government]] to provide {{INRConvert|10|b}} financing for food processing projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/yes-bank-signs-mou-with-govt-for-rs-1000-cr-financing/articleshow/61485872.cms|title=Yes Bank signs MoU with govt for Rs 1,000 cr financing|date=3 November 2017|publisher=|accessdate=11 April 2018|newspaper=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 moratorium ===\nOn 5 March 2020, the [[Reserve Bank of India]] (RBI) announced that, in the interest of its customers and depositors, it would suspend and supersede Yes Bank's board and impose a 30-day moratorium on its operations. The RBI cited Yes Bank's failures to raise new funding to cover its [[Non-performing loan|non-performing assets]], inaccurate statements of confidence in its ability to receive new funding, and its underreporting of its non-performing assets, among other factors, as the impetus for this moratorium. Customers are being limited from withdrawing more than {{INRConvert|50|k}} from their accounts, except in certain exceptional circumstances (such as to cover medical care, emergencies, higher education, and \"obligatory expenses\" for ceremonies such as weddings). RBI governor [[Shaktikanta Das]] stated that the matter would be resolved \"swiftly\"; [[Minister of Finance (India)|Finance Minister]] [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] announced a proposed turnaround plan, under which the [[State Bank of India]] would take a 49% stake in Yes Bank and introduce a new board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/yes-bank-crisis-rbi-sbi-invest-withdrawal-limit-reason-full-roundup-developments-1653193-2020-03-06|title=Yes Bank crisis: From what happens to my money to will SBI be saviour, all that has happened|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/business/2020/mar/06/here-is-all-you-need-to-know-about-the-yes-bank-moratorium-2113138.html|title=Here is all you need to know about the Yes Bank moratorium|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/yes-bank-withdrawal-limit-capped-at-rs-50000/articleshow/74498382.cms|title=Yes Bank withdrawal limit capped at Rs 50,000; RBI supersedes board|date=2020-03-06|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/yes-bank-withdrawal-limit-exceptions-1653068-2020-03-06|title=Yes Bank withdrawals capped at Rs 50,000. Do these exceptions apply to you?|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March 2020, [[ICRA Limited|ICRA]] downgraded the [[Bond credit rating|rating]] of Yes Bank's {{INRConvert|526|b}} in core bonds to a \"D\" rating, while [[Moody's]] downgraded them to \"Caa3\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/moodys-lowers-yes-bank-rating-to-caa3-from-b2/articleshow/74516990.cms|title=Moody\u2019s lowers YES Bank rating to \u2018Caa3\u2019 from \u2018B2\u2019|date=2020-03-06|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/icra-downgrades-yes-banks-rs-52600-crore-bonds-to-default/articleshow/74514255.cms|title=Icra downgrades YES Bank\u2019s Rs 52,600 crore bonds to \u2018default\u2019|date=2020-03-06|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> On 8 March 2020, Yes Bank founder Rana Kapoor was arrested by the [[Enforcement Directorate]] under charges of [[money laundering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zeenews.india.com/companies/yes-bank-founder-rana-kapoor-arrested-by-ed-in-money-laundering-case-2268416.html|title=Yes Bank founder Rana Kapoor arrested by ED in money laundering case|date=2020-03-08|website=Zee News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\nThe moratorium has caused major disruptions to e-commerce in India, due to a number of prominent services and online stores having used Yes Bank as its payment provider for UPI. Some services using Yes Bank in tandem with other payment providers have seen fewer disruptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2020/03/06/indias-yes-bank-breakdown-disrupts-walmarts-phonepe-among-a-dozen-other-services/|title=India\u2019s Yes Bank breakdown disrupts Walmart\u2019s PhonePe among a dozen other services|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2020, the Union Cabinet approved the reconstruction scheme for Yes Bank and that within three days of the notification of the scheme the moratorium would be lifted. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/cabinet-approves-reconstruction-scheme-for-yes-bank-fm-sitharaman-5030711.html|title=Cabinet approves reconstruction scheme for Yes Bank: FM Sitharaman|website=Moneycontrol|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> During this reconstruction, seven investors infused 12000 crore in Yes bank and Prashant Kumar has been proposed as new CEO of the bank. These investors include [[State Bank of India]], [[ICICI Bank]], [[HDFC Bank]], [[Axis Bank]], [[Kotak Mahindra Bank]], [[Rakesh Jhunjhunwala]], Radhakishan Damani and Azim Premji trust. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Shukla|first=Saloni|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/banking/seven-investors-join-sbi-to-put-over-rs-12000-cr-into-yes-bank-prashant-kumar-proposed-as-new-ceo/articleshow/74603685.cms|title=Seven investors join SBI to put over Rs 12,000 cr into Yes Bank; Prashant Kumar proposed as new CEO|date=2020-03-13|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-13|last2=Rebello|first2=Joel}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Banking in India]]\n* [[List of banks in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.yesbank.in/ Official Website]\n* [http://www.bseindia.com/stock-share-price/yes-bank-ltd/yes-bank/532648/ YES BANK] at [[Bombay Stock Exchange]]\n* [http://www.nseindia.com/live_market/dynaContent/live_watch/get_quote/GetQuote.jsp?symbol=YESBANK  BANK] at [[National Stock Exchange of India]]\n\n{{Banking in India}}\n\n[[Category:Private Sector Banks in India]]\n[[Category:Banks based in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Bombay Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:2005 initial public offerings]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:MD\u2192Managing director(2),SBI\u2192State Bank of India", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yes_Bank"}
{"title_page": "Patrick Munro", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Patrick Munro\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Patrick Munro\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date |1883|10|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Leeds]], [[England]]\n| death_date =  {{Death date and age |1942|05|3|1883|10|09|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Palace of Westminster]], [[London]], England\n| height = \n| weight = \n| ru_position = [[Half-back (rugby union)|Half Back]]\n| ru_amateuryears = -\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Oxford University RFC|Oxford University]]<br/>[[London Scottish F.C.|London Scottish]]\n| ru_amclubcaps =\n| ru_amclubpoints =\n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_province = \n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_nationalteam = [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]]\n| ru_nationalyears = 1905\u201311\n| ru_nationalcaps = 13\n| ru_nationalpoints = (14)\n| ru_ntupdate =\n| ru_coachclubs =\n| ru_coachyears =\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| ru_refereeyears = \n| ru_refereecomps =\n| ru_refereeapps = \n| ru_refereeupdate = \n| other =\n| occupation =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n| website =\n|module2= {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n   | office        = President of the Scottish Rugby Union\n   | term_start    = 1939\n   | term_end      = 1942\n   | predecessor        = [[William Halliday Welsh]]\n   | successor          = [[Harry Smith (rugby union)|Harry Smith]]\n   | prior_term         = \n   | order = 59th\n|module2= {{Infobox officeholder | embed = yes\n   |office=Member of Parliament\n|honorific_suffix=MP\n|constituency=Llandaff and Barry\n|country=United Kingdom|\nincumbent=1931-1942\n|death_cause =[[Killed in action]]\n|branch=Army\n|unit=Palace of Westminster Home Guard\n|rank=Private\n|spouse=Jessie Margaret Munro\n|parliamentarygroup=Conservative Party\n|battles=Second World War\n*[[Home Front (World War II)|Home Front]] {{KIA}}|awards=Order of the Nile}}\n }}\n}}\n'''Patrick Munro''' (9 October 1883 \u2013 3 May 1942), also known as '''Pat Munro''', was a [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] international [[rugby union]] player and later a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician<ref name=Scrum>Scrum.com player profile. Retrieved 20 February 2010</ref>\n\n==Rugby Union career==\n\n===Amateur career===\n\nHe was educated at [[Leeds Grammar School]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford]], where he held an Open History Scholarship and graduated with 2nd class Honours in History. He was also awarded a Half Blue for High Jump in 1906 and [[List of Presidents of Vincent's Club|President]] of the [[Vincent's Club]] (the club for Oxford Blues) in 1906\u20131907.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe played for [[Oxford University RFC]].<ref name=Bath1/>\n\nMunro was a [[Blue (university sport)|Rugby Blue]] in 1903,<ref name=\":0\" /> 1904, 1905 (and Captain in 1905){{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}.\n\nHe also played for [[London Scottish FC]].<ref name=Bath1/>\n\n===International career===\n\nHe was capped thirteen times for {{nrut|Scotland}} between 1905 and 1911<ref name=Scrum/><ref name=Bath1/> and was also a Rugby International for Scotland in 1905, 1906, 1907 and 1911. Munro also captained the team in 1907 and 1911.<ref name=Scrum />\n\n===Administrative career===\n\nHe was [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] for the period 1939 to 1942.<ref name=\"amazonaws\">{{cite web|url=https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/sru-files/files/SR_RR1819_digital.pdf|date=2018-08-16|title=Scottish Rugby Record 2018/19 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>.\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Sudan===\nHe joined the [[Anglo-Egyptian Sudan|Sudan Political Service]] in 1907, and was Governor of [[Darfur]] Province in 1923-1924 and Governor of [[Khartoum]] Province from 1925\u20131929.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe was [[mentioned in dispatches]] in 1919 and awarded the [[Order of the Nile]] (3rd class) in 1929.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was a Member of British Delegation to the [[Capitulations of the Ottoman Empire|Capitulations Conference]] in [[Montreux]] in 1937.<ref>[http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/other/dfat/treaties/1938/11.html Convention regarding the Abolition of the Capitulations in Egypt]</ref>\n\n===Member of Parliament===\n\nHe was Conservative [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Llandaff and Barry (UK Parliament constituency)|Llandaff and Barry]] from 1931 until his death. He was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to Capt. [[Euan Wallace]] when he was [[Under-Secretary of State for the Home Department]] in 1935 and then [[Secretary for Overseas Trade]]. Munro went on to be a Junior Government Whip in 1937, resigning in March 1942.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nJoining the government payroll as a Junior [[Lord of the Treasury]] later that year and serving until his death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/people/mr-patrick-munro/index.html|title=Mr Patrick Munro (Hansard)|website=api.parliament.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==Military Service and Death==\n\nMunro, a [[Private (rank)|Private]] in the [[Home Guard (United Kingdom)|Home Guard]], died on 3 May 1942 whilst taking part in a [[military exercise]] at [[Westminster]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/7531425|title=Casualty - Private Patrick Munro|website=www.cwgc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref><ref name=\"Bath1\">Bath, p109</ref> The exercise was a simulation of a landing by [[Airborne forces|airborne troops]] in central [[London]] in tandem with [[Fifth column|Fifth Column]] activities as a test of [[Home Guard (United Kingdom)|Home Guard]] defences.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Invasion of London|last=|first=|date=4 May 1942|work=The Times|access-date=|issue=49226|page=2}}</ref> As a member of the [[Palace of Westminster]] Home Guard, Munro was acting as a [[Runner (soldier)|runner]] and was in the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[Whip (politics)|Whips]]' room with two company colleagues. It was there that he collapsed suddenly and died before he could be taken for aid.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe is buried Cathedine (St. Michael) Churchyard in [[Brecknockshire]] under the care of the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Family==\n\nMunro was the fifth son of Patrick Munro<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Obituary|last=|first=|date=4 May 1942|work=The Times|access-date=|issue=49226|page=6}}</ref> and Mary Helen Catherine Dormond<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540891.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-229607|title=Munro, Patrick, (9 Oct. 1883\u20133 May 1942), MP (U) Llandaff and Barry, Glamorgan, since 1931; Junior Lord of the Treasury, 1937\u201342 {{!}}|last=|first=|date=1 December 2007|website=WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO|language=en|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.u229607|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 September 2019}}</ref>. \n\nMunro was married in 1911 to Jessie Margaret Munro of [[Bwlch]] in [[Wales]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of Scottish rugby union players killed in World War II]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n# Bath, Richard (ed.) ''The Scotland Rugby Miscellany'' (Vision Sports Publishing Ltd, 2007 {{ISBN|1-905326-24-6}})\n# Massie, Allan ''A Portrait of Scottish Rugby'' (Polygon, Edinburgh; {{ISBN|0-904919-84-6}})\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-patrick-munro | Patrick Munro }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Llandaff and Barry (UK Parliament constituency)|Llandaff and Barry]]\n  | years  = [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931]]&ndash;[[1942 Llandaff and Barry by-election|1942]]\n  | before = [[Charles Ellis Lloyd]]\n  | after  = [[Cyril Lakin]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munro, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Scots]]\n[[Category:British Home Guard soldiers]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for Welsh constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Cardiff constituencies]]\n[[Category:Ministers in the Churchill wartime government, 1940\u20131945]]\n[[Category:Oxford University RFC players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Leeds Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Scotland international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:SRU Presidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Patrick Munro\n| image = \n| caption =\n| birth_name = Patrick Munro\n| nickname =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date |1883|10|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Leeds]], [[England]]\n| death_date =  {{Death date and age |1942|05|3|1883|10|09|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Palace of Westminster]], [[London]], England\n| height = \n| weight = \n| ru_position = [[Half-back (rugby union)|Half Back]]\n| ru_amateuryears = -\n| ru_amateurclubs = [[Oxford University RFC|Oxford University]]<br/>[[London Scottish F.C.|London Scottish]]\n| ru_amclubcaps =\n| ru_amclubpoints =\n| ru_amupdate =\n| ru_provinceyears = \n| ru_province = \n| ru_provincecaps = \n| ru_provincepoints =\n| ru_nationalteam = [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]]\n| ru_nationalyears = 1905\u201311\n| ru_nationalcaps = 13\n| ru_nationalpoints = (14)\n| ru_ntupdate =\n| ru_coachclubs =\n| ru_coachyears =\n| ru_coachupdate =\n| ru_refereeyears = \n| ru_refereecomps =\n| ru_refereeapps = \n| ru_refereeupdate = \n| other =\n| occupation =\n| spouse =\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = \n| website =\n|module2= {{Infobox office