1907 and 1911. Munro also captained the team in 1907 and 1911.<ref name=Scrum />\n\n===Administrative career===\n\nHe was [[President of the Scottish Rugby Union|President]] of the [[Scottish Rugby Union]] for the period 1939 to 1942.<ref name=\"amazonaws\">{{cite web|url=https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/sru-files/files/SR_RR1819_digital.pdf|date=2018-08-16|title=Scottish Rugby Record 2018/19 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>.\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Sudan===\nHe joined the [[Anglo-Egyptian Sudan|Sudan Political Service]] in 1907, and was Governor of [[Darfur]] Province in 1923-1924 and Governor of [[Khartoum]] Province from 1925-1929.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe was [[mentioned in dispatches]] in 1919 and awarded the [[Order of the Nile]] (3rd class) in 1929.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was a Member of British Delegation to the [[Capitulations of the Ottoman Empire|Capitulations Conference]] in [[Montreux]] in 1937.<ref>[http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/other/dfat/treaties/1938/11.html Convention regarding the Abolition of the Capitulations in Egypt]</ref>\n\n===Member of Parliament===\n\nHe was Conservative [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Llandaff and Barry (UK Parliament constituency)|Llandaff and Barry]] from 1931 until his death. He was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to Capt. [[Euan Wallace]] when he was [[Under-Secretary of State for the Home Department]] in 1935 and then [[Secretary for Overseas Trade]]. Munro went on to be a Junior Government Whip in 1937, resigning in March 1942.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nJoining the government payroll as a Junior [[Lord of the Treasury]] later that year and serving until his death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/people/mr-patrick-munro/index.html|title=Mr Patrick Munro (Hansard)|website=api.parliament.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==Military Service and Death==\n\nMunro, a [[Private (rank)|Private]] in the [[Home Guard (United Kingdom)|Home Guard]], died on 3 May 1942 whilst taking part in a [[military exercise]] at [[Westminster]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/7531425|title=Casualty - Private Patrick Munro|website=www.cwgc.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref><ref name=\"Bath1\">Bath, p109</ref> The exercise was a simulation of a landing by [[Airborne forces|airborne troops]] in central [[London]] in tandem with [[Fifth column|Fifth Column]] activities as a test of [[Home Guard (United Kingdom)|Home Guard]] defences.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Invasion of London|last=|first=|date=4 May 1942|work=The Times|access-date=|issue=49226|page=2}}</ref> As a member of the [[Palace of Westminster]] Home Guard, Munro was acting as a [[Runner (soldier)|runner]] and was in the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[Whip (politics)|Whips]]' room with two company colleagues. It was there that he collapsed suddenly and died before he could be taken for aid.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe is buried Cathedine (St. Michael) Churchyard in [[Brecknockshire]] under the care of the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Family==\n\nMunro was the fifth son of Patrick Munro<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Obituary|last=|first=|date=4 May 1942|work=The Times|access-date=|issue=49226|page=6}}</ref> and Mary Helen Catherine Dormond<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540891.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-229607|title=Munro, Patrick, (9 Oct. 1883\u20133 May 1942), MP (U) Llandaff and Barry, Glamorgan, since 1931; Junior Lord of the Treasury, 1937\u201342 {{!}}|last=|first=|date=1 December 2007|website=WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO|language=en|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.u229607|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 September 2019}}</ref>. \n\nMunro was married in 1911 to Jessie Margaret Munro of [[Bwlch]] in [[Wales]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of Scottish rugby union players killed in World War II]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n# Bath, Richard (ed.) ''The Scotland Rugby Miscellany'' (Vision Sports Publishing Ltd, 2007 {{ISBN|1-905326-24-6}})\n# Massie, Allan ''A Portrait of Scottish Rugby'' (Polygon, Edinburgh; {{ISBN|0-904919-84-6}})\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-patrick-munro | Patrick Munro }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Llandaff and Barry (UK Parliament constituency)|Llandaff and Barry]]\n  | years  = [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931]]&ndash;[[1942 Llandaff and Barry by-election|1942]]\n  | before = [[Charles Ellis Lloyd]]\n  | after  = [[Cyril Lakin]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Munro, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Scots]]\n[[Category:British Home Guard soldiers]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for Welsh constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Cardiff constituencies]]\n[[Category:Ministers in the Churchill wartime government, 1940\u20131945]]\n[[Category:Oxford University RFC players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Leeds Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Scotland international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:SRU Presidents]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1906-1907 \u2192 1906\u20131907 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Munro"}
